# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chrysler
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In an effort that was led by Faisal of Saudi Arabia, the initial countries that OAPEC targeted were Canada, Japan, the Netherlands, the United Kingdom, and the United States.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] This list was later expanded to include Portugal, Rhodesia, and South Africa.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In March 1974, OAPEC lifted the embargo, but the price of oil had risen by nearly 300%: from US$3 per barrel ($19/m3) to nearly US$12 per barrel ($75/m3) globally.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Prices in the United States were significantly higher than the global average.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] After it was implemented, the embargo caused an oil crisis, or "shock", with many short- and long-term effects on the global economy as well as on global politics.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The 1973 embargo later came to be referred to as the **first oil shock**.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] A second oil shock occurred in 1979 in the aftermath of the Iranian Revolution.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Following the Israeli Declaration of Independence in 1948, there has been conflict between Arabs and Israelis in the Middle East, including several wars.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Suez Crisis, also known as the Second Arab–Israeli war, was sparked by Israel's southern port of Eilat being blocked by Egypt, which also nationalized the Suez Canal belonging to French and British investors.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] As a result of the war, the Suez Canal was closed for several months between 1956 and 1957.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Six-Day War of 1967 included an Israeli invasion of the Egyptian Sinai Peninsula, which resulted in Egypt closing the Suez Canal for eight years.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Following the Yom Kippur War, the canal was cleared in 1974 and opened again in 1975.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OAPEC countries cut production of oil and placed an embargo on oil exports to the United States after Richard Nixon requested $2.2 billion to support Israel's war effort.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nevertheless, the embargo lasted only until January 1974, though the price of oil remained high afterwards.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] By 1969, American domestic production of oil was peaking and could not keep pace with increasing demand from vehicles.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The US was importing 350 million barrels (56 million cubic metres) per year by the late 1950s, mostly from Venezuela and Canada.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Because of transportation costs and tariffs, it never purchased much oil from the Middle East.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1973, US production had declined to 16% of global output.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Eisenhower imposed quotas on foreign oil that would stay in place between 1959 and 1973.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Critics called it the "drain America first" policy.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Some scholars believe the policy contributed to the decline of domestic US oil production in the early 1970s.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The cheapness of oil compared with coal led to the decline of the coal industry.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1951, 51% of the United States' energy came from coal, and by 1973, only 19% of American industry was coal-based.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The decline in domestic oil production, combined with the country's increasing reliance on oil as a source of power, made the US economy vulnerable to a foreign oil embargo.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] When Richard Nixon became US president in 1969, he assigned George Shultz to head a committee to review the Eisenhower-era quota program.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Shultz's committee recommended that the quotas be abolished and replaced with tariffs, but Nixon decided to keep the quotas due to vigorous political opposition.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon imposed a price ceiling on oil in August 1971 as demand for oil was increasing and production was declining, which increased dependence on oil imports as consumption was bolstered by low prices.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1973, Nixon announced the end of the quota system.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Between 1970 and 1973 US imports of crude oil had nearly doubled, reaching 6.2 million barrels per day in 1973.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Until 1973, an abundance of oil supply had kept the market price of oil lower than the posted price.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1970, American oil production peaked and the United States began to import more oil.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Oil imports rose by 52% between 1969 and 1972.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] By 1972, 83% of the American oil imports came from the Middle East.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Throughout the 1960s, the price for a barrel of oil remained at $1.80, meaning that with the effects of inflation considered the price of oil in real terms got progressively lower throughout the decade, with Americans paying less for oil in 1969 than they had in 1959.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Even after a price for a barrel of oil rose to $2.00 in 1971, adjusted for inflation, people in the Western nations were paying less for oil in 1971 than they had in 1958.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The extremely low price of oil served as the basis for the "long summer" of prosperity and mass affluence that began in 1945.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC), was founded by five oil producing countries at a Baghdad conference on 14 September 1960.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The five founding members of OPEC were Venezuela, Iraq, Saudi Arabia, Iran and Kuwait.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OPEC was organized after the oil companies slashed the posted price of oil, but the posted price of oil remained consistently higher than the market price of oil between 1961 and 1972.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1963, the Seven Sisters controlled 86% of the oil produced by OPEC countries, but by 1970 the rise of "independent oil companies" had decreased their share to 77%.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The entry of three new oil producers—Algeria, Libya and Nigeria—meant that by 1970, 81 oil companies were doing business in the Middle East.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In the early 1960s Libya, Indonesia and Qatar joined OPEC.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OPEC was generally regarded as ineffective until political turbulence in Libya and Iraq strengthened their position in 1970.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Additionally, increasing Soviet influence provided oil producing countries with alternative means of transporting oil to markets.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Under the Tehran Price Agreement of 1971, signed on 14 February, the posted price of oil was increased and, due to a decline in the value of the US dollar relative to gold, certain anti-inflationary measures were enacted.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] A severe drain on US gold reserves lead to higher inflation and lack of confidence in the strength of the dollar, President Nixon issued Executive Order 11615 on August 15, 1971, which closed the gold window.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] This action made the dollar inconvertible to gold directly, except on the open market, and was soon dubbed the *Nixon Shock*, leading eventually to the collapse of the Bretton Woods system in 1976.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Because oil was priced in dollars, oil producers' real income decreased when the dollar started to float free of the old link to gold.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In September 1971, OPEC issued a joint communiqué stating that from then on, they would price oil in terms of a fixed amount of gold.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] After 1971, OPEC was slow to readjust prices to reflect this depreciation.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] From 1947 to 1967, the dollar price of oil had risen by less than two percent per year.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Until the oil shock, the price had also remained fairly stable versus other currencies and commodities.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OPEC ministers had not developed institutional mechanisms to update prices in sync with changing market conditions, so their real incomes lagged.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The substantial price increases of 1973–1974 largely returned their prices and corresponding incomes to former levels in terms of commodities such as gold.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Arab oil producing countries had attempted to use oil as leverage to influence political events on two prior occasions—the first was the Suez Crisis in 1956 when the United Kingdom, France and Israel invaded Egypt.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] During the conflict the Syrians sabotaged both the Trans-Arabian Pipeline and the Iraq–Baniyas pipeline, which disrupted the supply of oil to Western Europe.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The second instance was when war broke out between Egypt and Israel in 1967, but despite continued Egyptian and Syrian enmity against Israel, the embargo lasted only a few months.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Most scholars agree that the 1967 embargo was ineffective.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Although some members of the Organization of Arab Petroleum Exporting Countries (OAPEC) supported the use of oil as a weapon to influence the political outcome of the Arab–Israeli conflict, Saudi Arabia had traditionally been the strongest supporter of separating oil from politics.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Saudis were wary of the tactic due to the availability of oil from non-Arab oil producing countries, and in the decades leading up to the crisis, the region's conservative monarchies had grown dependent on Western support to ensure their continued survival as Nasserism gained traction.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On the other hand, Algeria, Iraq and Libya had strongly supported the use of oil as a weapon in the conflict.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Arab newspapers like the Egyptian *Al-Ahram*, Lebanese *An-Nahar* and Iraqi *Al-Thawra* had historically been supportive of the use of oil as a weapon.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1970, President Nasser of Egypt died and was succeeded by Anwar Sadat, a man who believed in the diplomacy of surprise, in engaging in sudden moves to upset the diplomatic equilibrium.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Sadat liked to say that his favourite game was backgammon, a game where skill and persistence was rewarded, but was best won by sudden gambles, making an analogy between how he played backgammon and conducted his diplomacy.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Under Nasser, Egypt and Saudi Arabia had engaged what was known as the Arab Cold War, but Sadat got along very well with King Faisal of Saudi Arabia, forming an alliance between the most populous Arab state and the wealthiest Arab state.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Unlike the secularist Nasser, Sadat was a pious Muslim and he had a strong personal rapport with King Faisal, who was an equally pious Muslim.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The man largely in charge of American foreign policy, the National Security Adviser, Henry Kissinger, later admitted that he was so engrossed with the Paris peace talks to end the Vietnam war that he and others in Washington missed the significance of the Egyptian-Saudi alliance.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At the same time that Sadat moved closer to Saudi Arabia, he also wanted a rapprochement with the United States and to move Egypt away from its alliance with the Soviet Union.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1971, the US had information that the Arab states were willing to implement another embargo.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In July 1972, Sadat expelled all 16,000 of the Soviet military personnel in Egypt in a signal that he wanted better relations with the United States.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger was taken completely by surprise by Sadat's move, saying: "Why has he done me this favor?
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] For Sadat, cost was no object as the money to buy Soviet arms came from Saudi Arabia.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At the same time, Faisal promised Sadat that if it should come to war, Saudi Arabia would embargo oil to the West.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In April 1973, the Saudi Oil Minister Ahmed Zaki Yamani visited Washington to meet Kissinger and told him that King Faisal was becoming more and more unhappy with the United States, saying he wanted America to pressure Israel to return all the lands captured in the Six Day War of 1967.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In a later interview, Yamani accused Kissinger of not taking his warning seriously, saying all he did was to ask him not to speak anymore of this threat.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Angry at Kissinger, Yamani, in an interview with the *Washington Post* on April 19, 1973, warned that King Faisal was considering an oil embargo.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At the time, the general feeling in Washington was the Saudis were bluffing and nothing would come of their threat to impose an oil embargo.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The fact that Faisal's ineffectual half brother King Saud had imposed a crippling oil embargo on Britain and France during the Suez War of 1956 was not considered an important precedent.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The CEOs of four of the United States' oil companies, after speaking with Faisal, arrived in Washington in May 1973 with the warning that Faisal was considerably tougher, more intelligent and more ruthless than his half-brother Saud whom he had deposed in 1964, and that his threats were serious.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger declined to meet the four CEOs.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In an assessment done by Kissinger and his staff about the Middle East in the summer of 1973, the repeated statements by Sadat about waging *jihad* against Israel were dismissed as empty talk, while the warnings from King Faisal were likewise regarded as inconsequential.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In September 1973, Nixon fired Rogers as Secretary of State and replaced him with Kissinger.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger later stated he had not been given enough time to know the Middle East, as he settled into the State Department's office at Foggy Bottom as Egypt and Syria attacked Israel on 6 October 1973.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 6 October 1973, the Yom Kippur began when Egypt attacked the Bar Lev Line in the Sinai Peninsula and Syria launched an offensive in the Golan Heights, both of which had been occupied by Israel during the 1967 Six-Day War.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal of Saudi Arabia was supportive, and on 8 October 1973, he told two Egyptian envoys: "You have made us all proud.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In the past we could not lift our heads up.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] He promised to give to Egypt a quality of aid worth $200 million US dollars to assist with the war effort, and stated he was willing to use the "oil weapon" if necessary to support Egypt.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The war began during the height of the Watergate scandal; as such Nixon largely let Kissinger manage foreign policy as he, Nixon, was distracted by the scandal.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger promised Israeli Prime Minister Golda Meir that the United States would replace its losses in equipment after the war.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon had ordered an arms lift to Israel on 12 October 1973, but Kissinger used the excuse of bureaucratic delays to limit the amount of weapons and ammunition sent to Israel.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Arab concept of the "peace of the brave", i.e. a victorious leader being magnanimous to his defeated opponents, meant there was a possibility that Sadat at least would make peace with Israel provided that the war ended in such a way that Egypt was not perceived to be defeated.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Likewise, Kissinger regarded Meir as being rather arrogant and believed that an armistice that ended the war in a manner that was not an unambiguous Israeli victory would make her more humble.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] As both Syria and Egypt lost much equipment during the fighting, the Soviet Union began to fly new equipment in, starting on 12 October.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Soviet flights to Syria and Egypt were recorded by the British radar stations in Cyprus.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Though the Soviets were flying in an average of 60 flights per day, exaggerated accounts appeared in Western newspapers speaking of "one hundred flights per day".
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At this point, both Nixon and Kissinger began to see the October War more in terms of the Cold War rather than Middle Eastern politics, both seeing the Soviet arms lifts to Egypt and Syria as a Soviet power play that required an American answer.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On October 12, 1973, US president Richard Nixon authorized Operation Nickel Grass, a strategic airlift to deliver weapons and supplies to Israel in order to replace its materiel losses.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The first American weapons to Israel arrived on 15 October 1973, and despite Nixon's orders the number of American planes flying into Tel Aviv were initially limited.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] After the first week of the war, the Israelis had halted the Syrian offensive in the Golan Heights and were pushing back the Syrians back towards Damascus.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Along the Suez canal, however, there was heavy fighting, with the Egyptians holding their own.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At an OPEC summit at the Sheraton Hotel in Kuwait City on 16 October 1973, it was announced the price of oil would go from $3.01 US dollars per barrel to $5.12 per barrel.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The news about the war on 16 October was grim from the Arab viewpoint, with the Syrians steadily being pushed back, while Israelis had opened a counter-offensive against the Egyptians and crossed the Great Bitter Lake.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Responses from stated representatives at the meeting were varied.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Saudi Oil Minister Ahmed Zaki Yamani stated, in a 1981 interview, that "[t]he king still wanted to give America a chance to stay out of the fighting.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] So we agreed to cut back production by just 5 percent per month.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] A full embargo, we agreed, was something we would implement only if we felt that things were absolutely hopeless".
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Iranian delegation left the summit after agreeing to the price increase, as the Shah of Iran only supported higher oil prices.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Oil Minister of Iraq, Sa'dun Hammadi demanded the "total nationalization" of all assets of American oil companies in the Middle East, the withdrawal of all Arab funds from the United States and for all Arab states to break diplomatic relations with the United States.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Libyan Oil Minister, Izz al-Din al-Mabruk, called for the nationalization of all the assets of all Western oil companies in the Middle East.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Saudi delegation led by Yemani, supported by the Algerian delegation, fought hard against the Iraqi and Libyan demands for an embargo, as Yemani maintained that forcing through an increase in the price of oil was the best way to influence the United States.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Hammadi and the rest of the Iraqi delegation left upset as Yemani had won over the majority of the delegations to the Saudi viewpoint.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The statement issued after midnight at the Sheraton Hotel was handwritten and, reflecting the tense talk, had several paragraphs crossed out while other paragraphs were written in by different hands.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 17 October, Arab oil producers cut production by 5% and threatened an oil embargo against Israel's wartime allies: the United States, the Netherlands, Rhodesia, South Africa, and Portugal.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 17–19 October 1973, the Saudi Foreign Minister, Omar Al Saqqaf, visited Washington together with the foreign ministers of Algeria, Kuwait and Morocco to warn that there was a real possibility of an oil embargo being imposed.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon promised him that the United States would mediate a settlement to the war that would be "peaceful, just and honorable" to both sides.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] He had ended the Vietnam war on what he felt was an honorable basis and now intended to end the October war in the same manner.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Saqqaf complained to King Faisal that Nixon seemed more interested in a dispute about "a burglary" (i.e. the Watergate scandal) than about the war.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] During a press conference, an American reporter mocked the threat of an embargo, contemptuously saying the Saudis "could drink their oil", leading Saqqaf to reply in anger "All right, we will!".
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Israel took heavy losses in men and materiel during the fighting against Egypt and Syria, and on 18 October 1973, Meir requested $850 million worth of American arms and equipment to replace its materiel losses.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon decided, characteristically, to act on an epic scale; Instead of the $850 million worth of arms requested, he sent a request to Congress for some $2.2 billion worth of arms to Israel, which was promptly approved.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon, whose administration was being badly battered by the Watergate scandal, felt that a bold foreign policy move might resuscitate his administration.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In an interview with the British historian Robert Lacey in 1981, Kissinger later admitted about the arms lift to Israel: "I made a mistake.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In retrospect it was not the best considered decision we made".
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The arms lift enraged King Faisal of Saudi Arabia.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal was angry that Israel had only asked for $850 million worth of American weapons, and instead received an unsolicited $2.2 billion worth of weapons, which he perceived as a sign of the pro-Israeli slant of American foreign policy.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal also felt insulted that Nixon had just promised Saqqaf an "honorable" peace the day before he submitted the request to Congress for some $2.2 billion worth of arms for Israel, which he saw as an act of duplicity on Nixon's part.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal had been opposed to a total embargo and only agreed to the 5% cut on 17 October under pressure from other Arab states.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal felt his efforts on behalf the United States were not being appreciated in Washington, which increased his fury at Nixon.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On the afternoon of 19 October 1973, Faisal was in his office when he learned about the United States sending $2.2 billion worth of weapons to Israel, and discussed the issue with two of his closest advisers, Abdullah ibn Abdul Rahman and Rashad Pharaon.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The king called Yamani at about 8 pm, and told him he was needed at the Riyassa Palace immediately.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Yamani told the king: "The TV news goes out at nine.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] If you make a decision now, we can get it announced at once".
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The king replied "Write this down" and announced he was placing a total embargo on the United States.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Most of the other oil-producing Arab states joined the embargo.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Algeria, Iraq, and Libya promoted the embargo, but did not actively enforce it.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The embargo was accompanied by gradual monthly production cuts—by December, production had been cut to 25% of September levels.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] This contributed to a global recession and increased tension between the United States and several of its European allies, who faulted the US for provoking an embargo by providing what many viewed as unconditional assistance to Israel.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OAPEC demanded a complete Israeli withdrawal from all territories beyond the 1949 Armistice border.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The embargo lasted from October 1973 to March 1974.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Because every Arab state except for Iraq and Libya joined the oil embargo, oil exports from the Middle East to the West were down by 60–70% by November 1973.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Japan and the nations of western Europe imported some 75% of their oil from the Near East.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The embargo led to immediate and sharp price raises, as Lacey noted that "competing desperately for dwindling supplies, consumers showed themselves willing to pay unparalleled money for their oil".
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Saudi Arabia had 25% of the world's oil reserves.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The embargo imposed on the United States led to shortages of oil in the United States, which set an inflationary spiral, as the new high prices for oil in the American market led to sharp increases of the price of oil in nations not subjected to the embargo.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] When the Iranian state oil company held an auction on 16 December 1973, bids for some $17 US dollars per barrel of oil were made.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In late December 1973, OPEC held a conference in Vienna when it was announced the price for a barrel of oil was to increase from $5 US dollars per barrel to $11.65 US dollars per barrel.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal was opposed to the price increase, which was largely the work of the Iranian delegation.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 22 February 1974, King Faisal chaired the second summit of Islamic states in Lahore, which, unlike the first summit that Faisal had chaired in 1969, was not boycotted by Iraq and Syria.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal was acclaimed as a conquering hero who humiliated and humbled the West by wrecking its economy.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The prime minister of Pakistan, Zulfikar Ali Bhutto, opened the conference by stating: "The armies of Pakistan are the armies of Islam.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On November 7, 1973, Kissinger flew to Riyadh to meet King Faisal and ask him to end the oil embargo in exchange for promising to be "evenhanded" with the Arab-Israeli dispute.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] As the plane carrying him prepared to land in Riyadh, Kissinger was clearly nervous at the prospect of negotiating with the stern Wahhabi Faisal who had a marked dislike of Jews.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] During a summit in Cairo the day before, Kissinger asked Sadat what Faisal was like and was told: "Well, Dr.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Henry, he will probably go on with you about Communism and the Jews".
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] King Faisal's two great hatreds were communism and Zionism, as he believed that the Soviet Union and Israel were plotting together against Islam.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Initially, Secretary of Defense James Schlesinger suggested to Kissinger that the USA invade Saudi Arabia and another Arab countries and seize their oil fields.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger stated in a private state department meeting that it's “ridiculous that the civilized world is held up by 8 million savages...
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Can’t we overthrow one of the sheikhs just to show that we can do it?” They formed a plan to invade Abu Dhabi, Kuwait, and Saudi Arabia.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger publicly threatened "countermeasures" in a November 21, 1973 press conference if the embargo was not lifted, and the Saudis responded with threatening further oil cuts and to burn their oil fields if the US military invaded.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] After the CIA confirmed these threats, Kissinger gave up military intervention and decided to deal with Israel's troop withdrawals, settling on diplomatic solutions to the oil embargo.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 18 March 1974, King Faisal ended the oil embargo.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Sadat had reported to Faisal that the United States was being more "evenhanded", and Kissinger had promised to sell Saudi Arabia weapons that it had previously denied under the grounds that they might be used against Israel.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Since Israeli forces did not withdraw to the 1949 Armistice Line, the majority of scholars believe that the embargo was a failure.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Roy Licklieder, in his 1988 book *Political Power and the Arab Oil Weapon*, concluded that the embargo was a failure because the countries that were targeted by the embargo did not change their policies on the Arab–Israeli conflict.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Licklieder believed that any long term changes were caused by the OPEC increase in the posted price of oil, and not the OAPEC embargo.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Daniel Yergin, on the other hand, has said that the embargo "remade the international economy".
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Over the long term, the oil embargo changed the nature of policy in the West towards increased exploration, alternative energy research, energy conservation and more restrictive monetary policy to better fight inflation.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p01] For further details see the "Energy crisis" series by Facts on File.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The effects of the embargo were immediate.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] OPEC forced oil companies to increase payments drastically.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The price of oil quadrupled by 1974 from US$3 to nearly US$12 per 42 gallon barrel ($75 per cubic meter), equivalent in 2018 dollars to a price rise from $17 to $61 per barrel.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Saudi Arabia had 25% of the world's oil, but only 4% of the oil used in the United States in 1973 came from the kingdom.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] However, Saudi Arabia plays an over-sized role within the Arab world.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In 1973, about 25% of the oil used in the United States came from Arab countries.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The shortage of oil within the United States caused by the Arab oil embargo forced prices to rise, which led price rises globally.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Oil producers that had not joined the embargo such as Iran, Venezuela, Libya and Iraq demanded higher prices in Japan and Europe, as an initiative to ship oil to those places instead of the United States, setting off a worldwide inflationary spiral.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Although the embargo did not severely disrupt US oil supplies—since Americans imported more oil from non-embargoed nations such as Iran—the resulting 400% increase in oil prices caused by the embargo damaged the American economy.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] A number of nations such as Venezuela, Nigeria, Iran and Iraq increased their oil production during the embargo, and sold their oil at a higher price.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The leader who pushed the most for higher oil prices was the Shah of Iran, and the Italian historian Giuliano Garavini has argued that the leader most responsible for the West's economic problems during the "oil shock" was not King Faisal, but rather the Shah.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Some of the nations that were classified as "friendly" to the Arab viewpoint in regards to the Arab-Israeli dispute such as France and Belgium were the ones who suffered the most from the worldwide inflation caused by the embargo.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In March 1974, the crisis eased when the embargo was lifted after negotiations at the Washington Oil Summit, but the effects lingered throughout the 1970s.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The dollar price of energy increased again in 1975, amid the weakening competitive position of the dollar in world markets.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Arab oil embargo ended the long period of prosperity in the West that had begun in 1945, throwing the world's economy into the steepest economic contraction since the Great Depression.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The "long summer" of prosperity in the post-war years had made possible the "swinging sixties" and the related rise of a rebellious youth culture, as it was easy to be hedonist or in rebellion against traditional values in a time of unprecedented prosperity.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] 1945 to 1973 had been a period of unprecedented prosperity in the West, a "long summer" that many believed would never end.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Its abrupt end in 1973, as the oil embargo increased the price of oil by 400% within a matter of days and threw the world's economy into a sharp recession, with unemployment mounting and inflation raging, came as a profound shock.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The end of what the French called the *Trente Glorieuses* ("Glorious Thirty" [years]) led to widespread pessimism in the West, with the *Financial Times* running a famous headline in late 1973 saying, "The Future will be subject to Delay".
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In an August 1974 address to the General Assembly, Kurt Waldheim, the secretary-general of the United Nations, complained about "the note of helplessness and fatalism creeping into world affairs".
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The sudden and abrupt end of the "long summer" of prosperity in 1973-1974 played a major role in the pessimistic mood that characterized the culture of the West of the 1970s.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In 1975, a report to Congress from the Federal Energy Administration estimated that the embargo of 1973–1974 had caused about 500,000 Americans to lose their jobs, and caused a GNP loss between $10 billion–$20 billion.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] This price increase had a dramatic effect on oil exporting nations, for the countries of the Middle East who had long been dominated by the industrial powers were seen to have taken control of a vital commodity.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil-exporting nations began to accumulate vast wealth.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Some of the income was dispensed in the form of aid to other underdeveloped nations whose economies had been caught between higher oil prices and lower prices for their own export commodities, amid shrinking Western demand.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Much went for arms purchases that exacerbated political tensions, particularly in the Middle East.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The 400% increase in the world oil prices led to extravagant promises being made by the leaders of oil-producing nations.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Shah of Iran told his subjects in a speech in December 1973 that he was launching "Great Civilization" project that would make Iran into a First World nation by the 1990s.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] President Carlos Andrés Pérez of Venezuela likewise launched his *Le Gran Venezuela* project intended to make Venezuela into a First World nation.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] President Yakubu Gowon of Nigeria told his people that henceforward Nigeria's main problem would be "managing abundance".
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] After the oil shock, Nigeria presented itself as the first African nation that would reach First World status.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In Lagos, a series of stately modernist buildings were erected as appropriate for a nation that saw itself as the leader of all Black Africa.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Much of the oil wealth in Nigeria was stolen by corrupt politicians.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] At least some of Nigeria's new oil wealth went to rebuild the areas devastated by the civil war of 1967-1970 and to address the complaints that too much of Nigeria's oil wealth went to the federal government in Lagos instead of the people.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The new wealth generated by the "oil shock" allowed for Chairman Houari Boumédiène of Algeria to become a global leader, courted by elites in the First World and the Third World.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil embargo led a sudden interest in the Palestinian issue.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Between 1973 and 1981, Saudi Arabia donated a sum worth $1 billion US dollars to the Palestine Liberation Organization, which thus had a budget that exceeded that of many Third World nations.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On November 8, 1973, Kissinger became the first Secretary of State to meet with a Saudi leader since 1953, as he met King Faisal to ask him to end the embargo.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Within two week of the embargo being launched, all of the foreign ministers of the nations of the European Economic Community, now the European Union, met in a conference to issue a statement calling for Israel "to end the territorial occupation which has maintained since the conflict of 1967".
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On December 11, 1973, the Japanese Foreign Minister Masayoshi Ōhira flew in to Riyadh to meet King Faisal for "talks on improving bilateral relations".
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Shortly afterwards, the French foreign minister Michel Jobert arrived to sign an agreement that provided oil for France for the next twenty years.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On January 24, 1974, as the Shah of Iran, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, was coming off the ski slopes of St.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Moritz, he was met by the British Chancellor of Exchequer, Anthony Barber, and the Trade Secretary, Peter Walker.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In a role-reversal, Barber and Walker paid homage to the Shah, who promised them that his nation would sell the United Kingdom 5 million tons of oil in exchange for some £100 million of British goods, to aid his plans to industrialize Iran.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Saudi Arabia experienced an upsurge of prosperity and affluence after the oil embargo, whose consequences horrified King Faisal.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Faisal, who was devoted to a harsh puritanical strain of Sunni Islam known in the West as Wahhabism, was appalled by the way that his subjects became materialistic, devoted only to conspicuous consumption and greed as they lost interest in Islam.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Lacey wrote: "The spiritual dangers of easy affluence distressed him more.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] His simple gesture of piety and honor seemed to have opened a Pandora's Box that threatened to turn his realm into a parody of all he held dear".
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In the last two of years of his life, Faisal fell into depression over the way his subjects had been seduced into a consumerist lifestyle, becoming lost in a sense of "melancholia".
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Faisal's son, Crown Prince Mohammad told Lacey in 1981: "The profligacy, the greed, he felt he could not stem it.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] He become so bound up in his work, there was almost nothing private of him left".
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] A sign of the changed values was that despite the total ban on alcohol in Saudi Arabia, drinking and drug use became common with the younger members of the House of Saud.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] James Akins, the American ambassador in Riyadh reported; "the sky over Riyadh is black with vultures with new get-richer-quicker plans under their wings".
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In 1974, property prices in Riyadh doubled on a weekly basis for the entire year, as the prosperity led to a real estate speculation bubble that was often compared to the Klondike gold rush of 1898–1899.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] At the Red Sea port of Jeddah, there were so many ships queuing up laden with cement for the construction boom in Saudi Arabia, that construction contractors hired helicopters to fly the cement in, twenty bags per flight.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] A number of families engaged in the Saudi construction industry such as the Juffali, Alireza, al-Khasshoggi and the bin Laden families all became very wealthy as a result of the construction boom.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The period after the oil shock of 1973–1974 is still fondly remembered in Saudi Arabia as the "age of abundance", where nearly everyone had a significant increase in their standard of living.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The wealth and corruption generated by the oil shock led to a fundamentalist backlash in Saudi Arabia.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On 20 November 1979, Islam's holiest shrine, the Grand Mosque of Mecca, was seized by a group who proclaimed themselves to be the followers of the Mahdi, a messianic figure said to appear at the dawn of every Muslim century to strike down the enemies of Islam.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The leader of the uprising, Juhayman al-Otaybi, read out a list of grievances, as he accused the House of Saud of being corrupt and degenerate, listing by name a number of Saudi princes who were engaged in dubious business dealings and/or who drank alcohol.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Saudi Army recaptured the Grand Mosque, and the surviving "renegades", as the rebels were labelled, were executed.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In Algeria, the "oil shock" led to the establishment of a welfare state where none had existed previously.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The lower oil prices of the 1980s along with cutbacks and the belief that the FLN regime was corrupt helped cause the riots of October 1988 against the FLN regime, that killed at least 500 people.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The riots were largely caused by the fact that the low oil prices had forced the Algerian state to end many of its more generous social policies between 1986 and 1988, leading to an unemployment rate of 30% by 1988, along with the knowledge that the FLN regime had stolen millions.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In the aftermath of the October riots, President Chadli Bendjedid began a transition to democracy.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The first free elections in Algeria in January 1992 were won by the Islamist FIS, which led to a military coup and an outbreak of a civil war that killed hundreds of thousands of Algerians.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] OPEC-member states raised the prospect of nationalization of oil company holdings.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Most notably, Saudi Arabia nationalized Aramco in 1980 under the leadership of Saudi oil minister Ahmed Zaki Yamani.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] As other OPEC nations followed suit, the cartel's income soared.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Saudi Arabia undertook a series of ambitious five-year development plans.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The biggest began in 1980, funded at $250 billion.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Other cartel members also undertook major economic development programs.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Control of oil became known as the "oil weapon".
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] It came in the form of an embargo and production cutbacks from the Arab states.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The weapon was aimed at the United States, Great Britain, Canada, Japan and the Netherlands.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] These target governments perceived that the intent was to push them towards a more pro-Arab position.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] However, the affected countries did not undertake dramatic policy changes.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The risk that the Middle East could become another superpower confrontation with the USSR was of more concern to Washington than oil.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Further, interest groups and government agencies more worried about energy were no match for Kissinger's dominance.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The embargo had a negative influence on the US economy, causing immediate demands to address the threats to US energy security.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On an international level, the price increases changed competitive positions in many industries, such as automobiles.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Macroeconomic problems consisted of both inflationary and deflationary impacts.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The embargo left oil companies searching for new ways to increase oil supplies, even in rugged terrain such as the Arctic.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Finding oil and developing new fields usually required five to 10 years before significant production.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The average US retail price of a gallon of regular gasoline rose 43% from 38.5¢ in May 1973 to 55.1¢ in June 1974.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] State governments asked citizens not to put up Christmas lights.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Oregon banned Christmas and commercial lighting altogether.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Politicians called for a national gasoline rationing program.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Nixon asked gasoline retailers to voluntarily not sell gasoline on Saturday nights or Sundays.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] 90% of gas station owners complied, which produced long lines of motorists wanting to fill up their cars while they still could.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The "oil shock" provided considerable impetus to the American nuclear industry as a way to achieve "energy independence" from the Middle East.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On 7 November 1973, Nixon in an address to Congress called for Project Independence to make the United States self-sufficient in energy by 1980, which called for a massive investment in the nuclear industry.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Nixon envisioned nuclear energy as more economical, and was encouraged by the enthusiasm of many officials who saw nuclear energy as the technology of the future.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By the late 1960s, a lively environmentalist movement had emerged in the United States, and the Project Independence nuclear program was the subject of much debate in both the media and Congress.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The ensuing debates revealed that many of the claims made for nuclear power underestimated the true costs of nuclear reactors.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Equally problematic was where to safety store the spent nuclear rods that emitted a toxic level of radioactivity for centuries afterward, in a cost-effective manner.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The issue of the spent nuclear rods was especially difficult because of NIMBYism, where communities proved unwilling to accept a storage place for the inevitable by-product of nuclear power, the spent nuclear rods, with the demand that the government find some other community to store the rods.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Many of the nuclear reactors ordered in 1973 were cancelled due to cost overruns, while over 100 nuclear plants were shut down as uneconomical over the next 10 years.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Unlike nations that tried to use nuclear power as a way for energy independence such as France and Sweden, the United States had substantial reserves of its own oil, which weakened the case for nuclear power in the ensuring debates.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By 1989, only 18% of American energy came from nuclear power plants, which was a fraction of what Project Independence had envisioned in 1973.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil shock led to anti-Arab feelings becoming common.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Cartoons published in American newspapers during the oil shock depicted Arabs as disgusting, ugly, obese, corrupt and greedy.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In the cartoons, the long hooked Semitic noses that had traditionally been featured in anti-Jewish cartoons were applied to the Arab sheiks as a way to illustrate their supposed greed.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] American public opinion did not see the use of the "oil weapon" as due to politics, and tended to explain the embargo as only due to the excessive greed of King Faisal and the other Arab leaders, hence the use of the hooked Semitic nose in the cartoons as a sort of shorthand for insatiable greed.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Soviet Union was not a beneficiary of the oil crisis.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The crisis prompted the USSR to raise energy prices within the Council on Mutual Economic Assistance (CMEA).
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The embargo was not uniform across Western Europe.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Of the nine members of the European Economic Community (EEC), the Netherlands faced a complete embargo.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By contrast Britain and France received almost uninterrupted supplies.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] That was their reward for refusing to allow the US to use their airfields and stopping arms and supplies to both the Arabs and the Israelis.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The other six EEC nations faced partial cutbacks.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The UK had traditionally been an ally of Israel, and Harold Wilson's government supported the Israelis during the Six-Day War.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] His successor, Ted Heath, reversed this policy in 1970, calling for Israel to withdraw to its pre-1967 borders.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The devalued franc made imports more expensive for French consumers, which encouraged them to buy French products, while making French products cheaper abroad.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] France was entirely dependent upon imported oil, through French companies continued to lease the oil concessions in Algeria until 1971.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The low price of oil internationally compensated to a certain extent for the higher price of oil caused by the devaluation.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The devalued franc ensured that the dramatic price increases caused by the oil shock hit the French economy especially hard in 1973.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The UK, Germany, Italy, Switzerland and Norway banned flying, driving and boating on Sundays.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Sweden rationed gasoline and heating oil.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Netherlands imposed prison sentences for those who used more than their ration of electricity.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The EEC was unable to achieve a common policy during the first month of the embargo.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] It issued a statement on November 6, after the embargo and price rises had begun.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] It was widely viewed as pro-Arab, supporting the Franco-British line on the war.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] OPEC duly lifted its embargo from all EEC members.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The other European states did not rally in defense of the Dutch who were left to fend for themselves and instead reached bilateral deals with Saudi Arabia, Iraq and Iran.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Faced with a recession, there was a tendency within the EEC nations to turn inwards away from European integration.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The price rises had a much greater impact in Europe than the embargo.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The crisis retarded the movement towards European economic integration which had been gathering pace ever since the EEC, now the European Union, had been founded in 1957.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In 1973, the German historian Jens-Uwe Wunderlich wrote that attempts to finish off the European common market came to a "complete standstill" in 1973 and it was not until 1977 that movement towards creating the common market resumed.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In particular, the oil shock increased the appeal of nuclear energy as a way to achieve energy independence from the turbulent Middle East.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Starting in March 1974 with the "Energy Plan" introduced by the premier Pierre Messmer, the French state made a massive investment in nuclear energy.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By the 1990s, 80% of all of France's energy came from nuclear plants.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The North Sea oil fields, which were discovered in 1969, did not start to be exploited until 1975, making the United Kingdom entirely dependent upon imported oil in 1973.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The way that world oil prices quadrupled in late 1973 had a very adverse impact on the British economy,.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In a series of speeches in December 1973, the Prime Minister Edward Heath warned that because of the oil shock that the British economy was going into recession and the British people should expect economic austerity.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Heath offered the coal miners a 7% wage increase, which was rejected as insufficient by the miners who went on strike.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Through not subjected to the embargo, the UK faced an energy crisis of its own—a series of strikes by coal miners and railroad workers over the winter of 1973–74 became a major factor in the defeat of Heath's Conservative government in the February 1974 general elections.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The new Labour government told the British to heat only one room in their houses over the winter.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Labour government of Harold Wilson settled the strike by giving the coal miners a 35% pay increase.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Japan was hard hit, since it imported 90% of its oil from the Middle East.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] It had a stockpile good for 55 days, and another 20-day supply was en route.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Facing its most serious crisis since 1945, the government ordered a 10% cut in the consumption of industrial oil and electricity.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In December 1973, it ordered an immediate 20% cut in oil use and electric power to Japan's major industries, and cutbacks in leisure automobile usage.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Economist predicted the growth rate would plunge from 5% annually, down to zero or even negative territory.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Seeking to take advantage of the crisis, Japanese business called on the government to relax its controls on air pollution and water pollution.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Moscow tried to take advantage by promising energy assistance if Japan renounced its claim to the Kurile Islands.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Instead it made $3.3 billion of dollars in loans to the Arab states and called on Israel to step back.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Japan's defensive strategy was explained to Kissinger when he met with top leaders in Tokyo in November 1973.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In the long run Japan never wavered in its determination to maintain very strong close ties to the United States, while in self-defense briefly providing the Arab powers with the rhetoric they demanded in return for resuming oil shipments in early 1974.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] To assure future oil flows, Japan added suppliers outside of the Middle East, invested in nuclear power, imposed conservation measures, and provided funding for Arab governments and the Palestinians.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The crisis was a major factor in the long-run shift of Japan's economy away from oil-intensive industries.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Japanese auto makers benefited from the crisis.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The jump in gasoline prices helped their small, fuel-efficient models to gain market share from the "gas-guzzling" Detroit competition.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] This triggered a drop in US sales of American cars that lasted into the 1980s.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil crisis contributed to the poor state of the Indian economy and played a role in Indira Gandhi's decision to impose The Emergency, a dictatorship.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The state led a push for coal as an energy source, even though there were reservations about its adverse environmental effects.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil shock destroyed the economy of South Vietnam.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] A spokesman for President Nguyễn Văn Thiệu admitted in a TV interview that the government was being "overwhelmed" by the inflation caused by the oil shock.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] An American businessman living in Saigon stated after the oil shock, that attempting to make money in South Vietnam was "like making love to a corpse".
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In December 1973, Vietcong sappers attacked and destroyed the petroleum depot of Nha Be, further depleting fuel sources.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By the summer of 1974, the US embassy in Saigon reported that morale in the ARVN (Army of the Republic of Vietnam) had fallen to dangerously low levels and it was uncertain how much more longer South Vietnam would last.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] As inflation eroded the value of the South Vietnamese *đồng*, it became common by the summer of 1974 to see ARVN soldiers and their families begging in the streets for food.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In December 1974, the North Vietnamese PAVN (People's Army of Vietnam) launched an offensive in the Central Highlands that was far more successful than expected, due to the ARVN's low morale and weak resistance.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On March 1, 1975, the PAVN launched a major offensive that quickly overran the Central Highlands.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Following their victory in the Central Highlands, the North Vietnamese launched the "Ho Chi Minh Campaign" that captured Saigon on April 30, 1975.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Three of the nations targeted by the embargo were located in southern Africa or had colonies there.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Portugal which ruled the colonies of Angola, Portuguese Guiana (modern Guinea-Bissau), and Portuguese East Africa (modern Mozambique) had fighting colonial wars in all of its African colonies since the 1960s with Angola being the first to rise up in 1961.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Angola is rich in oil, which protected Portugal from the worse of the embargo.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] But the economic stability of the *Estado Novo* regime was damaged by the worldwide inflation, which help cause the Carnation Revolution which toppled the *Estado Novo* regime in April 1974 and led to the restoration of democracy.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Portugal granted independence to all of its colonies except for Macau in 1975.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The British historian Rob Skinner wrote the embargo had a "significant impact" on the South African economy.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The inflationary rise in commodity prices increased the input costs of South African manufacturing, making South African manufactured goods uncompetitive on the world market.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The rise in the price of gold as a hedge against inflation (South Africa has the world's largest gold mines) caused the *rand* to increase in value, which caused further problems for South African manufacturing.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The strategy pursued by the National Party government since 1948 of sponsoring the industrialization of South Africa was derailed by the oil shock, with what Skinner described as "important social and political consequences" for the *apartheid* regime.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Soweto uprising of 1976 was at least in part caused by anger at the high unemployment rate in the black South African community.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Even worse hit than South Africa was Rhodesia (modern Zimbabwe), where oil was already expensive as the white supremacist government of Rhodesia had been under United Nations sanctions since 1965, and thus the smugglers who sold Rhodesia oil charged a premium for their services.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The premium charged by the "sanctions busters" such as Iran increased after the embargo, which threw the Rhodesian economy into recession.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Despite the United Nations sanctions, Rhodesia was a major exporter of chrome, steel and tobacco with the United States exempting "strategical" Rhodesian products such as chrome from the sanctions.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The global recession of 1973–1975 proved more effective than the United Nations in ending the global demand for Rhodesian products, which made the Rhodesian recession especially severe.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Unlike South Africa, which had a sizable and long-standing white population, the white population of Rhodesia was much smaller and more recent.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Rhodesia depended considerably more than South Africa on white immigration to provide enough soldiers for its army, while most of the Rhodesian whites had only arrived in the 1950s and did not have very deep roots in the country.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The white flight caused by the recession put the Rhodesian Army at a major disadvantage in its war against the black guerrillas.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The war cost the Rhodesian government one million Rhodesian dollars per day by 1975, and the costs of the war threatened to bankrupt Rhodesia.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1979, Rhodesia signed the Lancaster House Agreement, which led to Black majority rule in 1980.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Price controls exacerbated the crisis in the US.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The system limited the price of "old oil", that which had already been discovered, while allowing newly discovered oil to be sold at a higher price, to encourage investment.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As a result, old oil was withdrawn from the market, creating greater scarcity.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The rule also discouraged development of alternative energies.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The rule had been intended to promote oil exploration.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Scarcity was addressed by rationing, as in many countries.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Motorists faced long lines at gas stations beginning in summer 1972 and increasing by summer 1973.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] A sign of the change caused by the crisis was that in 1974 the Exxon oil company replaced the General Motors corporation to be the largest corporation in the world, as measured by gross sales revenues.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Simon as the first Administrator of the Federal Energy Office, a short-term organization created to coordinate the response to the embargo.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Simon allocated states the same amount of domestic oil for 1974 that each had consumed in 1972, which worked for states whose populations were not increasing.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In other states, lines at gasoline stations were common.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The American Automobile Association reported that in the last week of February 1974, 20% of American gasoline stations had no fuel.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Odd–even rationing allowed vehicles with license plates having an odd number as the last digit, or a vanity license plate, to buy gas only on odd-numbered days of the month.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Others could buy only on even-numbered days.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In some states, a three-color flag system was used to denote gasoline availability at service stations—green for unrationed availability, yellow for restricted/rationed sales, and red for out of stock.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Rationing led to violent incidents, when truck drivers chose to strike for two days in December 1973 over the limited supplies that Simon had allocated for their industry.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In Pennsylvania and Ohio, non-striking truckers were shot at by striking truckers.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In Arkansas, trucks of non-strikers were attacked with bombs.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] America had controlled the price of natural gas since the 1950s.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] With the inflation of the 1970s, the price was too low to encourage the search for new reserves.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] America's natural gas reserves dwindled from 237 trillion in 1974 to 203 trillion in 1978.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The price controls were not changed, despite president Gerald Ford's repeated requests to Congress.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] To help reduce consumption, in 1974 a national maximum speed limit of 55 mph (89 km/h) was imposed through the Emergency Highway Energy Conservation Act.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Development of the Strategic Petroleum Reserve began in 1975, and in 1977 the cabinet-level Department of Energy was created, followed by the National Energy Act of 1978.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In November 1995, President Bill Clinton signed the National Highway Designation Act, ending the federal 55 mph speed limit, which allowed states to restore their prior maximum speed limit.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Year-round daylight saving time was implemented from January 6, 1974, to October 27, 1975, with a break between October 27, 1974, and February 23, 1975, when the country observed standard time.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Parents complained that it forced many children to travel to school before sunrise.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The crisis prompted a call to conserve energy, most notably a campaign by the Advertising Council using the tagline "Don't Be Fuelish".
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Many newspapers carried advertisements featuring cut-outs that could be attached to light switches, reading "Last Out, Lights Out: Don't Be Fuelish".
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Although not regulated by the new legislation, auto racing groups voluntarily began conserving.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1974, NASCAR reduced all race distances by 10%; the 24 Hours of Daytona and the 12 Hours of Sebring race were cancelled.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1975, the Energy Policy and Conservation Act was passed, leading to the creation of the Corporate Average Fuel Economy (CAFE) standards that required improved fuel economy for cars and light trucks.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1976, Congress created the Weatherization Assistance Program to help low-income homeowners and renters reduce their demand for heating and cooling through better insulation.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1980, domestic luxury cars with a 130-inch (3.3 m) wheelbase and gross weights averaging 4,500 pounds (2,041 kg) were no longer made.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The automakers had begun phasing out the traditional front engine/rear-wheel drive layout in compact cars in favor of lighter front engine/front-wheel drive designs.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] A higher percentage of cars offered more efficient four-cylinder engines.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Domestic auto makers also began offering more fuel efficient diesel powered passenger cars as well.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The energy crisis led to greater interest in renewable energy, nuclear power and domestic fossil fuels.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 2013, Peter Grossman opined that American energy policies after the crisis became and remained dominated by crisis-mentality thinking, promoting expensive quick fixes and single-shot solutions that ignore market and technology realities.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] He wrote that instead of providing stable rules that support basic research while leaving plenty of scope for entrepreneurship and innovation, Congresses and presidents repeatedly backed policies which promised politically expedient solutions whose true prospects were doubtful.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The Brazilian government implemented its Proálcool (pro-alcohol) project in 1975 that mixed ethanol with gasoline for automotive fuel.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Israel was one of the few countries unaffected by the embargo, since it could extract sufficient oil from the Sinai.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] But to supplement Israel's over-taxed power grid, Harry Zvi Tabor, the father of Israel's solar industry, developed the prototype for a solar water heater now used in over 90% of Israeli homes.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Western central banks decided to sharply cut interest rates to encourage growth, deciding that inflation was a secondary concern.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Although this was the orthodox macroeconomic prescription at the time, the resulting stagflation surprised economists and central bankers.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The policy is now considered by some to have deepened and lengthened the adverse effects of the embargo.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Recent research claims that in the period after 1985 the economy became more resilient to energy price increases.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The price shock created large current account deficits in oil-importing economies.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] A petrodollar recycling mechanism was created, through which OPEC surplus funds were channeled through the capital markets to the West to finance the current account deficits.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The functioning of this mechanism required the relaxation of capital controls in oil-importing economies.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] It marked the beginning of an exponential growth of Western capital markets.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In the United States in 1974, seven of the 15 top Fortune 500 companies were oil companies, falling to four in 2014.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The crisis had a major impact on international relations and created a rift within NATO.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Some European nations and Japan sought to disassociate themselves from United States foreign policy in the Middle East to avoid being targeted by the boycott.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Arab oil producers linked any future policy changes to peace between the belligerents.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] To address this, the Nixon Administration began multilateral negotiations with the combatants.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] They arranged for Israel to pull back from the Sinai Peninsula and the Golan Heights.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By January 18, 1974, US Secretary of State Henry Kissinger had negotiated an Israeli troop withdrawal from parts of the Sinai Peninsula.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The promise of a negotiated settlement between Israel and Syria was enough to convince Arab oil producers to lift the embargo in March 1974. and again during the 1979 energy crisis.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] America's Cold War policies suffered a major blow from the embargo.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] They had focused on China and the Soviet Union, but the latent challenge to US hegemony coming from the Third World became evident.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 2004, declassified documents revealed that the US was so distraught by the rise in oil prices and being challenged by underdeveloped countries that they briefly considered military action to forcibly seize Middle Eastern oilfields in late 1973.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Western Europe began switching from pro-Israel to more pro-Arab policies.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] This change strained the Western alliance.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The US, which imported only 12% of its oil from the Middle East (compared with 80% for the Europeans and over 90% for Japan), remained staunchly committed to Israel.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The percentage of US oil which comes from the nations bordering the Persian Gulf remained steady over the decades, with a figure of a little more than 10% in 2008.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] With the embargo in place, many developed countries altered their policies regarding the Arab-Israeli conflict.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] These included the UK, which refused to allow the United States to use British bases and Cyprus to airlift resupplies to Israel, along with the rest of the members of the European Community.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Canada shifted towards a more pro-Arab position after displeasure was expressed towards Canada's mostly neutral position.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] "On the other hand, after the embargo the Canadian government moved quickly indeed toward the Arab position, despite its low dependence on Middle Eastern oil".
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Although lacking historical connections to the Middle East, Japan was the country most dependent on Arab oil.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] 71% of its imported oil came from the Middle East in 1970.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] On November 7, 1973, the Saudi and Kuwaiti governments declared Japan a "nonfriendly" country, to encourage it to change its noninvolvement policy.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] It received a 5% production cut in December, causing a panic.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] On November 22, Japan issued a statement "asserting that Israel should withdraw from all of the 1967 territories, advocating Palestinian self-determination, and threatening to reconsider its policy toward Israel if Israel refused to accept these preconditions".
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By December 25, Japan was considered an Arab-friendly state.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The oil embargo was announced roughly one month after a right-wing military coup in Chile led by General Augusto Pinochet toppled socialist president Salvador Allende on September 11, 1973.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The response of the Nixon administration was to propose doubling arms sales.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As a consequence, an opposing Latin American bloc was organized and financed in part by Venezuelan oil revenues, which quadrupled between 1970 and 1975.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The oil shock disrupted the status quo relationships between Arab countries and the US and USSR.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] At the time, Egypt, Syria and Iraq were allied with the USSR.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Saudi Arabia, Turkey and Iran, plus Israel, aligned with the US.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Vacillations in alignment often resulted in greater support from the respective superpowers.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] When Anwar Sadat became president of Egypt in 1970, he dismissed Soviet specialists in Egypt and reoriented towards the US.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Concerns over economic domination from increased Soviet oil production turned into fears of military aggression after the 1979 Soviet invasion of Afghanistan, a major turning point in Cold War geopolitics.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Persian Gulf states turned toward the US for security guarantees against Soviet military action, coming at a time marked by increased American weapons sales, technology, and outright military presence to various US-allied nations.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Saudi Arabia and Iran became increasingly dependent on American security assurances to manage both external and internal threats, including increased military competition between them over increased oil revenues.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Both states were competing for preeminence in the Persian Gulf, and using increased revenues to fund expanded militaries.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1979, Saudi arms purchases from the US were five times larger than Israel's.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Saudi Arabia is a near-absolute monarchy, an Arabic speaking country, and has a Sunni Muslim majority, while Persian speaking Iran since 1979 is an Islamist theocracy with a Shiite Muslim majority, which explains the current hostility between Saudi Arabia and Iran.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The oil crisis sent a signal to the auto industry globally, which changed many aspects of production and usage for decades to come.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] After World War II, most West European countries taxed motor fuel to limit imports, and as a result most cars made in Europe were smaller and more economical than their American counterparts.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By the late 1960s, increasing incomes supported rising car sizes.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The oil crisis pushed West European car buyers away from larger, less economical cars.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The most notable result of this transition was the rise in popularity of compact hatchbacks.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The only notable small hatchbacks built in Western Europe before the oil crisis were the Peugeot 104, Renault 5 and Fiat 127.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By the end of the decade, the market had expanded with the introduction of the Ford Fiesta, Opel Kadett (sold as the Vauxhall Astra in Great Britain), Chrysler Sunbeam and Citroën Visa.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Buyers looking for larger cars were increasingly drawn to medium-sized hatchbacks.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Virtually unknown in Europe in 1973, by the end of the decade they were gradually replacing sedans as the mainstay of this sector.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Between 1973 and 1980, medium-sized hatchbacks were launched across Europe: the Chrysler/Simca Horizon, Fiat Ritmo (Strada in the UK), Ford Escort MK3, Renault 14, Volvo 340 / 360, Opel Kadett, and Volkswagen Golf.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] These cars were considerably more economical than the traditional saloons they were replacing, and attracted buyers who traditionally bought larger vehicles.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Some 15 years after the oil crisis, hatchbacks dominated most European small and medium car markets, and had gained a substantial share of the large family car market.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Before the energy crisis, large, heavy, and powerful cars were popular.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1971, the standard engine in a Chevrolet Caprice was a 400-cubic inch (6.5 liter) V8.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The wheelbase of this car was 121.5 inches (3,090 mm), and *Motor Trend*'s 1972 road test of the similar Chevrolet Impala achieved no more than 15 highway miles per gallon.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In the 15 years prior to the 1973 oil crisis, gasoline prices in the US had lagged well behind inflation.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The crisis reduced the demand for large cars.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Japanese imports became mass-market leaders with unibody construction and front-wheel drive, which became de facto standards.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] From Europe, the Volkswagen Beetle, the Volkswagen Fastback, the Renault 8, the Renault LeCar, and the Fiat Brava were successful.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Detroit responded with the Ford Pinto, the Ford Maverick, the Chevrolet Vega, the Chevrolet Nova, the Plymouth Valiant and the Plymouth Volaré.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] American Motors sold its homegrown Gremlin, Hornet and Pacer models.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] A decade after the 1973 oil crisis, Honda, Toyota and Nissan, affected by the 1981 voluntary export restraints, opened US assembly plants and established their luxury divisions (Acura, Lexus and Infiniti, respectively) to distinguish themselves from their mass-market brands.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Compact trucks were introduced, such as the Toyota Hilux and the Datsun Truck, followed by the Mazda Truck (sold as the Ford Courier), and the Isuzu-built Chevrolet LUV.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Mitsubishi rebranded its Forte as the Dodge D-50 a few years after the oil crisis.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Mazda, Mitsubishi and Isuzu had joint partnerships with Ford, Chrysler, and GM, respectively.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Later, the American makers introduced their domestic replacements (Ford Ranger, Dodge Dakota and the Chevrolet S10/GMC S-15), ending their captive import policy.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] An increase in imported cars into North America forced General Motors, Ford and Chrysler to introduce smaller and fuel-efficient models for domestic sales.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The Dodge Omni / Plymouth Horizon from Chrysler, the Ford Fiesta and the Chevrolet Chevette all had four-cylinder engines and room for at least four passengers by the late 1970s.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1985, the average American vehicle moved 17.4 miles per gallon, compared to 13.5 in 1970.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The improvements stayed, even though the price of a barrel of oil remained constant at $12 from 1974 to 1979.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Sales of large sedans for most makes, except Chrysler products, recovered within two model years of the 1973 crisis.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The Cadillac DeVille and Fleetwood, Buick Electra, Oldsmobile 98, Lincoln Continental, Mercury Marquis, and various other luxury oriented sedans became popular again in the mid-1970s.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The only full-size models that did not recover were lower price models such as the Chevrolet Bel Air and Ford Galaxie 500.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Slightly smaller models such as the Oldsmobile Cutlass, Chevrolet Monte Carlo, Ford Thunderbird and various others sold well.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Economical imports succeeded alongside heavy, expensive vehicles.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1976, Toyota sold 346,920 cars (average weight around 2,100 lbs), while Cadillac sold 309,139 cars (average weight around 5,000 lbs).
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Federal safety standards, such as NHTSA Federal Motor Vehicle Safety Standard 215 (pertaining to safety bumpers), and compacts like the 1974 Mustang I were a prelude to the DOT "downsize" revision of vehicle categories.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1977, GM's full-sized cars reflected the crisis.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1979, virtually all "full-size" American cars had shrunk, featuring smaller engines and smaller outside dimensions.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Chrysler ended production of their full-sized luxury sedans at the end of the 1981 model year, moving instead to a full front-wheel drive lineup for 1982, except for the M-body Dodge Diplomat/Plymouth Gran Fury and Chrysler New Yorker Fifth Avenue sedans.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] OPEC soon lost its preeminent position, and in 1981, its production was surpassed by that of other countries.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Additionally, its own member nations were divided.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Saudi Arabia, trying to recover market share, increased production, pushing prices down, shrinking or eliminating profits for high-cost producers.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The world price, which had peaked during the 1979 energy crisis at nearly $40 per barrel, decreased during the 1980s to less than $10 per barrel.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Adjusted for inflation, oil briefly fell back to pre-1973 levels.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] This "sale" price was a windfall for oil-importing nations, both developing and developed.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] During the Iran–Iraq War of 1980–1988, the stated war aim of Iran was to overthrow the Baath regime in Iraq.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As a consequence, Saudi Arabia and the other Arab Gulf states leaned in a very pro-Iraqi neutrality during the war.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As a part of its policy of supporting Iraq, Saudi Arabia pumped out oil in massive quantities to lower the price as a way of hurting Iran's economy.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The low price of oil also hurt Iraq's economy, which forced Iraq to borrow massive sums of money, putting Iraq deeply into debt.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In contrast, Iran refused to borrow any money because of its refusal to pay interest on any loans, and paid the costs of the war directly from the sale of its oil.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Iran's revenue from the sale of oil went from $20 billion US dollars per year in 1982 to $5 billion US dollars per year by 1988, which pushed Iran to the verge of bankruptcy and forced Iran to make peace with Iraq later in 1988.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] During the war, the Iranian delegation at OPEC tried very hard to have the group cut production to raise prices, but were blocked by the other delegations led by the Saudi delegation, who insisted on more oil production.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The embargo encouraged new venues for energy exploration, including Alaska, the North Sea, the Caspian Sea, and the Caucasus.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Exploration in the Caspian Basin and Siberia became profitable.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Cooperation changed into a far more adversarial relationship as the USSR increased its production.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1980, the Soviet Union had become the world's largest producer.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Part of the decline in prices and economic and geopolitical power of OPEC came from the move to alternative energy sources.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] OPEC had relied on price inelasticity to maintain high consumption, but had underestimated the extent to which conservation and other sources of supply would eventually reduce demand.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Electricity generation from nuclear power and natural gas, home heating from natural gas, and ethanol-blended gasoline all reduced the demand for oil.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The drop in prices presented a serious problem for oil-exporting countries in northern Europe and the Persian Gulf.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Heavily populated, impoverished countries, whose economies were largely dependent on oil—including Mexico, Nigeria, Algeria, and Libya—did not prepare for a market reversal that left them in sometimes desperate situations.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] When reduced demand and increased production glutted the world market in the mid-1980s, oil prices plummeted and the cartel lost its unity.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Mexico (a non-member), Nigeria, and Venezuela, whose economies had expanded in the 1970s, faced near-bankruptcy, and even Saudi Arabian economic power was significantly weakened.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The divisions within OPEC made concerted action more difficult.
[src:chrysler/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As of 2015, OPEC has never approached its earlier dominance.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] From the mid-1980s to September 2003, the inflation-adjusted price of a barrel of crude oil on NYMEX was generally under US$25/barrel in 2008 dollars.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] Commentators attributed these price increases to multiple factors, including Middle East tension, soaring demand from China, the falling value of the U.S. dollar, reports showing a decline in petroleum reserves, worries over peak oil, and financial speculation.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] For a time, geopolitical events and natural disasters had strong short-term effects on oil prices, such as North Korean missile tests, the 2006 conflict between Israel and Lebanon, worries over Iranian nuclear plans in 2006, Hurricane Katrina, and various other factors.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] By 2008, such pressures appeared to have an insignificant impact on oil prices given the onset of the global recession.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] The recession caused demand for energy to shrink in late 2008, with oil prices collapsing from the July 2008 high of $147 to a December 2008 low of $32.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] However, it has been disputed that the laws of supply and demand of oil could have been responsible for an almost 80% drop in the oil price within a six-month period.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] Oil prices stabilized by August 2009 and generally remained in a broad trading range between $70 and $120 through November 2014, before returning to 2003 pre-crisis levels by early 2016, as US production increased dramatically.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] The United States went on to become the largest oil producer by 2018.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] The price of crude oil in 2003 traded in a range between $20–$30/bbl.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] Between 2003 and July 2008, prices steadily rose, reaching $100/bbl in late 2007, coming close to the previous inflation-adjusted peak set in 1980.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] A steep rise in the price of oil in 2008 – also mirrored by other commodities – culminated in an all-time high of $147.27 during trading on 11 July 2008, more than a third above the previous inflation-adjusted high.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] High oil prices and economic weakness contributed to a demand contraction in 2007–2008.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] In the United States, gasoline consumption declined by 0.4% in 2007, then fell by 0.5% in the first two months of 2008 alone.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] Detailed analysis of changes in oil price from 1970–2007.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] World crude oil demand grew an average of 1.76% per year from 1994 to 2006, with a high of 3.4% in 2003–2004.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] World demand for oil is projected to increase 37% over 2006 levels by 2030, according to the 2007 U.S.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] Energy Information Administration's (EIA) annual report.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] In 2007, the EIA expected demand to reach an ultimate high of 118 million barrels per day (18.8×10^6 m3/d), from 2006's 86 million barrels (13.7×10^6 m3), driven in large part by the transportation sector.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] A 2008 report from the International Energy Agency (IEA) predicted that although drops in petroleum demand due to high prices have been observed in developed countries and are expected to continue, a 3.7 percent rise in demand by 2013 is predicted in developing countries.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] This is projected to cause a net rise in global petroleum demand during that period.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] Transportation consumes the largest proportion of energy, and has seen the largest growth in demand in recent decades.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] This growth has largely come from new demand for cars and other personal-use vehicles powered by internal combustion engines.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] This sector also has the highest consumption rates, accounting for approximately 55% of oil use worldwide as documented in the Hirsch report and 68.9% of the oil used in the United States in 2006.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] Cars and trucks are predicted to cause almost 75% of the increase in oil consumption by India and China between 2001 and 2025.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] In 2008, auto sales in China were expected to grow by as much as 15–20 percent, resulting in part from economic growth rates of over 10 percent for five years in a row.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] Demand growth is highest in the developing world, but the United States is the world's largest consumer of petroleum.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] China, by comparison, increased consumption from 3.4 million barrels (540,000 m3) a day to 7 million barrels (1,100,000 m3) a day, an increase of 3.6 million barrels (570,000 m3) a day, in the same time frame.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] Per capita, annual consumption is 24.85 barrels (3.951 m3) by people in the US, 1.79 barrels (0.285 m3) in China, and 0.79 barrels (0.126 m3) in India.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] As countries develop, industry, rapid urbanization and higher living standards drive up energy use, most often of oil.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] Thriving economies such as China and India are quickly becoming large oil consumers.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] China has seen oil consumption grow by 8% yearly since 2002, doubling from 1996–2006.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] Although swift continued growth in China is often predicted, others predict that China's export-dominated economy will not continue such growth trends due to wage and price inflation and reduced demand from the US.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] India's oil imports are expected to more than triple from 2005 levels by 2020, rising to 5 million barrels per day (790×10^3 m3/d).
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] Another large factor on petroleum demand has been human population growth.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] Because world population grew faster than oil production, production per capita peaked in 1979 (preceded by a plateau during the period of 1973–1979).
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] The world’s population in 2030 is expected to be double that of 1980.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] State fuel subsidies shielded consumers in multiple nations from higher market prices, but a number of these subsidies were reduced or removed as the governmental cost rose.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] An important contributor to the price increase was the slowdown in oil supply growth, which has been a general trend since oil production surpassed new discoveries in 1980.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] The likelihood that global oil production will decline at some point, leading to lower supply, is a long-term fundamental cause of rising prices.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] Although there is contention about the exact time at which global production will peak, a majority of industry participants acknowledge that the concept of a production peak is valid.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] However, some commentators argued that global warming awareness and new energy sources would limit demand before the effects of supply could, suggesting that reserve depletion would be a non-issue.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] A large factor in the lower supply growth of petroleum has been that oil's historically high ratio of Energy Returned on Energy Invested is in significant decline.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] Petroleum is a limited resource, and the remaining accessible reserves are consumed more rapidly each year.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] Remaining reserves are increasingly difficult to extract and therefore more expensive.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] Eventually, reserves will only be economically feasible to extract at extremely high prices.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] Even if total oil supply does not decline, increasing numbers of experts believe the easily accessible sources of light sweet crude are almost exhausted and in the future the world will depend on more-expensive unconventional oil reserves and heavy crude oil, as well as renewable energy sources.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] It is thought by a number of people, including energy economists such as Matthew Simmons, that prices could continue to rise indefinitely until a new market equilibrium is reached at which point supply satisfies worldwide demand.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] Timothy Kailing, in a 2008 *Journal of Energy Security* article, pointed out the difficulty of increasing production in mature petroleum regions, even with vastly increased investment in exploration and production.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] By looking at the historical response of production to variation in drilling effort, he claimed that very little increase of production could be attributed to increased drilling.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] This was due to a tight quantitative relationship of diminishing returns with increasing drilling effort: As drilling effort increased, the energy obtained per active drill rig was reduced according to a severely diminishing power law.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] This analysis suggested that even an enormous increase of drilling effort was unlikely to lead to significantly increased oil and gas production in a mature petroleum region like the United States.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] A prominent example of investment in non-conventional sources is seen in the Canadian oil sands.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] They are a far less cost-efficient source of heavy, low-grade oil than conventional crude; but when oil trades above $60/bbl, the tar sands become attractive to exploration and production companies.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] While Canada's oil sands region is estimated to contain as much "heavy" oil as all the world's reserves of "conventional" oil, efforts to economically exploit these resources lag behind the increasing demand of recent years.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] Until 2008, CERA (a consulting company wholly owned by energy consultants IHS Energy) did not believe this would be such an immediate problem.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] However, in an interview with *The Wall Street Journal,* Daniel Yergin, previously known for his quotes that the price of oil would soon return down to "normal", amended the company's position on 7 May 2008 to predict that oil would reach $150 during 2008, due to tightness of supply.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] This reversal of opinion was significant, as CERA, among other consultancies, provided price projections that were used by multiple official bodies to plan long-term strategy in respect of energy mix and price.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] Other major energy organisations, such as the International Energy Agency (IEA), had already been much less optimistic in their assessments for some time.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] In 2008, the IEA drastically accelerated its prediction of production decline for existing oilfields, from 3.7% a year to 6.7% a year, based largely on better accounting methods, including actual research of individual oil field production throughout the world.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] Terrorist and insurgent groups have increasingly targeted oil and gas installations, and succeeded in stopping a substantial volume of exports during the 2003–2008 height of the American occupation of Iraq.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] Such attacks are sometimes perpetrated by militias in regions where oil wealth has produced few tangible benefits for the local citizenry, as is the case in the Niger Delta.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] A number of factors have resulted in possible and/or actual concerns about the reduced supply of oil.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] The post-9/11 war on terror, labor strikes, hurricane threats to oil platforms, fires and terrorist threats at refineries, and other short-lived problems are not solely responsible for the higher prices.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] Such problems do push prices higher temporarily, but have not historically been fundamental to long-term price increases.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] Investment demand for oil occurs when investors purchase *futures contracts* to buy a commodity at a set price for future delivery.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] "Speculators are not buying any actual crude. ...
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] Several claims have been made implicating financial speculation as a major cause of the price increases.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] In May 2008 the transport chief for Germany's Social Democrats estimated that 25 percent of the rise to $135 a barrel had nothing to do with underlying supply and demand.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] Senate committee in May indicating that "demand shock" from "institutional investors" had increased by 848 million barrels (134,800,000 m3) over the previous five years, almost as much as the increased physical demand from China (920 million barrels (146,000,000 m3)).
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] The influence of institutional investors, such as sovereign wealth funds, was also discussed in June 2008, when Lehman Brothers suggested that price increases were related to increases in exposure to commodities by such investors.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] In June 2008, OPEC's Secretary General Abdallah Salem el-Badri stated that current world consumption of oil at 87 million bpd was far exceeded by the "paper market" for oil, which equaled about 1.36 billion bpd, or more than 15 times the actual market demand.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] An interagency task force on commodities markets was formed in the U.S. government to investigate the claims of speculators' influence on the petroleum market.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] The task force concluded in July 2008 that "market fundamentals" such as supply and demand provided the best explanations for oil price increases, and that increased speculation was not statistically correlated with the increases.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] The report also noted that increased prices with an elastic supply would cause increases in petroleum inventories.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] As inventories actually declined, the task force concluded that market pressures were most likely to blame.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] Other commodities that were not subject to market speculation (such as coal, steel, and onions) saw similar price increases over the same time period.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] In June 2008 U.S. energy secretary Samuel Bodman said that insufficient oil production, not financial speculation, was driving rising crude prices.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] He said that oil production had not kept pace with growing demand.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] "In the absence of any additional crude supply, for every 1% of crude demand, we will expect a 20% increase in price in order to balance the market," Bodman said.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] This contradicted earlier statements by Iranian OPEC governor Mohammad-Ali Khatibi indicating that the oil market was saturated and that an increase in production announced by Saudi Arabia was "wrong".
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] In September 2008, Masters Capital Management released a study of the oil market, concluding that speculation did significantly impact the price.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] The study stated that over $60 billion was invested in oil during the first six months of 2008, helping drive the price per barrel from $95 to $147, and that by the beginning of September, $39 billion had been withdrawn by speculators, causing prices to fall.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] There is debate over what the **effects of the 2000s energy crisis** will be over the long term.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] Some speculated that an oil-price spike could create a recession comparable to those that followed the 1973 and 1979 energy crises or a potentially worse situation such as a global oil crash.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] Increased petroleum prices are reflected in a vast number of products derived from petroleum, as well as those transported using petroleum fuels.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] In addition to high oil prices, from year 2000 volatility in the price of oil has increased notably and this volatility has been suggested to be a cause of the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] The perceived increase in oil price differs internationally according to currency market fluctuations and the purchasing power of currencies.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] On average, oil prices roughly quadrupled for these areas, triggering widespread protest activities.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] A similar price surge for petroleum-based fertilizers contributed to the 2007–08 world food price crisis and further unrest.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] In 2008, a report by Cambridge Energy Research Associates stated that 2007 had been the year of peak gasoline usage in the United States, and that record energy prices would cause an "enduring shift" in energy consumption practices.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] According to the report, in April gas consumption had been lower than a year before for the sixth straight month, suggesting 2008 would be the first year U.S. gasoline usage declined in 17 years.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] The total miles driven in the U.S. began declining in 2006.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] In the United States, oil prices contributed to inflation averaging 3.3% in 2005–2006, significantly above the average of 2.5% in the preceding 10-year period.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] As a result, during this period the Federal Reserve steadily raised interest rates to curb inflation.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] High oil prices typically affect less-affluent countries first, particularly the developing world with less discretionary income.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] There are fewer vehicles per capita, and oil is often used for electricity generation as well as private transport.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] The World Bank has looked more deeply at the effect of oil prices in the developing countries.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] One analysis found that in South Africa a 125 percent increase in the price of crude oil and refined petroleum reduces employment and GDP by approximately 2 percent, and reduces household consumption by approximately 7 percent, affecting mainly the poor.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] OPEC's annual oil export revenue surged to a new record in 2008, estimated around US$800 billion.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] According to informed observers, OPEC, meeting in early December 2007, seemed to desire a high but stable price that would deliver substantial needed income to the oil-producing states, but avoid prices so high that they would negatively impact the economies of the oil-consuming nations.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] A range of US$70–80 per barrel was suggested by some analysts to be OPEC's goal.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] In November 2008, as prices fell below $60 a barrel, the IEA warned that falling prices could lead to both a lack of investment in new sources of oil and a fall in production of more-expensive unconventional reserves such as the oil sands of Canada.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] The IEA's chief economist warned, "Oil supplies in the future will come more and more from smaller and more-difficult fields," meaning that future production requires more investment every year.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] A lack of new investment in such projects, which had already been observed, could eventually cause new and more-severe supply issues than had been experienced in the early 2000s according to the IEA.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] Because the sharpest production declines had been seen in developed countries, the IEA warned that the greatest growth in production was expected to come from smaller projects in OPEC states, raising their world production share from 44% in 2008 to a projected 51% in 2030.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] The IEA also pointed out that demand from the developed world may have also peaked, so that future demand growth was likely to come from developing nations such as China, contributing 43%, and India and the Middle East, each about 20%.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] By the beginning of September 2008, prices had fallen to $110.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] OPEC Secretary General El-Badri said that the organization intended to cut output by about 500,000 barrels (79,000 m3) a day, which he saw as correcting a "huge oversupply" due to declining economies and a stronger U.S. dollar.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] On 10 September, the International Energy Agency (IEA) lowered its 2009 demand forecast by 140,000 barrels (22,000 m3) to 87.6 million barrels (13,930,000 m3) a day.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] As countries throughout the world entered an economic recession in the third quarter of 2008 and the global banking system came under severe strain, oil prices continued to slide.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] In November and December, global demand growth fell, and U.S. oil demand fell an estimated 10% overall from early October to early November 2008 (accompanying a significant drop in auto sales).
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] In their December meeting, OPEC members agreed to reduce their production by 2.2 million barrels (350,000 m3) per day, and said their resolution to reduce production in October had an 85% compliance rate.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] Petroleum prices fell below $35 in February 2009, but by May 2009 had risen back to mid-November 2008 levels around $55.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] The global economic downturn left oil-storage facilities with more oil than in any year since 1990, when Iraq's invasion of Kuwait upset the market.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] In early 2011, crude oil rebounded above US$100/bbl due to the Arab Spring protests in the Middle East and North Africa, including the 2011 Egyptian revolution, the 2011 Libyan civil war, and steadily tightening international sanctions against Iran.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] The oil price fluctuated around $100 through early 2014.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] By 2014–2015, the world oil market was again steadily oversupplied, led by an unexpected near-doubling in U.S. oil production from 2008 levels due to substantial improvements in shale "fracking" technology.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] By January 2016, the OPEC Reference Basket fell to US$22.48/bbl – less than one-sixth of its record from July 2008 ($140.73), and back below the April 2003 starting point ($23.27) of its historic run-up.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] OPEC production was poised to rise further with the lifting of Iranian sanctions, at a time when markets already appeared to be oversupplied by at least 2 million barrels per day.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] In mainstream economic theory, a free market rations an increasingly scarce commodity by increasing its price.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] A higher price should stimulate producers to produce more, and consumers to consume less, while possibly shifting to substitutes.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] The first three mitigation strategies in the above list are, therefore, in keeping with mainstream economic theory, as government policies can affect the supply and demand for petroleum as well as the availability of substitutes.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] In contrast, the last type of strategy in the list (attempting to shield consumers from rising prices) would seem to work against classical economic theory, by encouraging consumers to overconsume the scarce quantity, thus making it even scarcer.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] To avoid creating outright shortages, attempts at price control may require some sort of rationing scheme.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] Economists say that the substitution effect will spur demand for alternate fossil fuels, such as coal or liquefied natural gas and for renewable energy, such as solar power, wind power, and advanced biofuels.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] For example, China and India are currently heavily investing in natural gas and coal liquefaction facilities.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] Nigeria is working on burning natural gas to produce electricity instead of simply flaring the gas, where all non-emergency gas flaring will be forbidden after 2008.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] Outside the U.S., more than 50% of oil is consumed for stationary, non-transportation purposes such as electricity production where it is relatively easy to substitute natural gas for oil.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] Oil companies including the supermajors have begun to fund research into alternative fuel.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] BP has invested half a billion dollars for research over the next several years.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] The motivations behind such moves are to acquire the patent rights as well as understanding the technology so vertical integration of the future industry could be achieved.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] The rise in oil prices caused renewed interest in electric cars, with several new models hitting the market, both hybrid and purely electric.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] The most successful among the former being the Toyota Prius and among the latter the cars of companies like Tesla.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] Several countries also incentivized the use of electric cars through tax-breaks or subsidies or by building charging stations.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] In a similar vein as the original TGV that was switched from gas turbine to electric propulsion after the 1973 oil crisis, several countries have renewed and increased their efforts for electric propulsion in their rail systems, specifically high-speed rail.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] In the time since 2003, the global High speed rail network almost doubled and there are plans globally that amount to the network being doubled again within the next ten to twenty years, based on current constructions.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] China in particular went from having no high-speed rail whatsoever in 2003 to having the longest network in the world in 2015.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] Another major factor in petroleum demand is the widespread use of petroleum products such as plastic.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] These could be partially replaced by bioplastics, which are derived from renewable plant feedstocks such as vegetable oil, cornstarch, pea starch, or microbiota.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] They are used either as a direct replacement for traditional plastics or as blends with traditional plastics.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] The most common end use market is for packaging materials.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] Japan has also been a pioneer in bioplastics, incorporating them into electronics and automobiles.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] Bioasphalt can also be used as a replacement of petroleum asphalt.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] The United States Strategic Petroleum Reserve could, on its own, supply current U.S. demand for about a month in the event of an emergency, unless it were also destroyed or inaccessible in the emergency.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] This could potentially be the case if a major storm were to hit the Gulf of Mexico, where the reserve is located.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] While total consumption has increased, the western economies are less reliant on oil than they were twenty-five years ago, due both to substantial growth in productivity and the growth of sectors of the economy with little oil dependence such as finance and banking, retail, etc.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] The decline of heavy industry and manufacturing in most developed countries has reduced the amount of oil per unit GDP; however, since these items are imported anyway, there is less change in the oil dependence of industrialized countries than the direct consumption statistics indicate.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] One recourse used and discussed in the past to avoid the negative impacts of oil shocks in the a number of developed countries which have high fuel taxes has been to temporarily or permanently suspend these taxes as fuel costs rise.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] France, Italy, and the Netherlands lowered taxes in 2000 in response to protests over high prices, but other European nations resisted this option because public service finance is partly based on energy taxes.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] The issue came up again in 2004, when oil reached $40 a barrel causing a meeting of 25 EU finance ministers to lower economic growth forecasts for that year.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] Because of budget deficits in several countries, they decided to pressure OPEC to lower prices instead of lowering taxes.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] In 2007, European truckers, farmers, and fishermen again raised concerns over record oil prices cutting into their earnings, hoping to have taxes lowered.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] In the United Kingdom, where fuel taxes were raised in October and were scheduled to rise again in April 2008, there was talk of protests and roadblocks if the tax issue was not addressed.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] On 1 April 2008, a 25 yen per liter fuel tax in Japan was allowed to lapse temporarily.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] This method of softening price shocks is even less viable to countries with much lower gas taxes, such as the United States.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] Locally decreasing fuel tax can decrease fuel prices, but globally prices are set by supply and demand, and therefore fuel tax decreases may have no effect on fuel prices, and fuel tax increases might actually decrease fuel prices by reducing demand.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] But this depends on the price elasticity of demand for fuel which is -0.09 to -0.31, meaning that fuel is a relatively inelastic commodity, i.e. increasing or decreasing prices have overall only a small effect on demand and therefore price change.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] Transportation demand management has the potential to be an effective policy response to fuel shortages or price increases and has a greater probability of long term benefits than other mitigation options.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] There are major differences in energy consumption for private transport between cities; an average U.S. urban dweller uses 24 times more energy annually for private transport as a Chinese urban resident.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] These differences cannot be explained by wealth alone but are closely linked to the rates of walking, cycling, and public transport use and to enduring features of the city including urban density and urban design.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] For individuals, remote work provides alternatives to daily commuting and long-distance air travel for business.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] Technologies such as videoconferencing, e-mail, and corporate wikis, continue to improve.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] As the cost of moving human workers continues to rise, while the cost of moving information electronically continues to fall, presumably market forces should cause more people to substitute virtual travel for physical travel.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] Matthew Simmons explicitly calls for "liberating the workforce" by changing the corporate mindset from paying people to show up physically to work every day, to paying them instead for the work they do, from any location.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] This would allow more information workers to work from home either part-time or full-time, or from satellite offices or Internet cafes near to where they live, freeing them from long daily commutes to central offices.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] However, even full adoption of remote work by all eligible workers might only decrease energy consumption by about 1% (with present energy savings estimated at 0.01–0.04%).
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] By comparison, a 20% increase in automobile fuel economy would save 5.4%.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] The price rises of mid-2008 led to a variety of proposals to change the rules governing energy markets and energy futures markets, in order to prevent rises due to market speculation.
[src:chrysler/2000s-energy-crisis] On 26 July 2008, the United States House of Representatives passed the Energy Markets Emergency Act of 2008 (H.R.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] World food prices increased dramatically in 2007 and the first and second quarter of 2008, creating a global crisis and causing political and economic instability and social unrest in both poor and developed nations.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Although the media spotlight focused on the riots that ensued in the face of high prices, the ongoing crisis of food insecurity had been years in the making.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Systemic causes for the worldwide increases in food prices continue to be the subject of debate.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] After peaking in the second quarter of 2008, prices fell dramatically during the late-2000s recession but increased during late 2009 and 2010, reaching new heights in 2011 and 2012 (see 2010–2012 world food price crisis) at a level slightly higher than the level reached in 2008.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Over the next years, prices fell, reaching a low in March 2016 with the deflated Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) food price index close to the pre-crisis level of 2006.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] The initial causes of the late-2006 price spikes included droughts in grain-producing nations and rising oil prices.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Oil price increases also caused general escalations in the costs of fertilizers, food transportation, and industrial agriculture.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Root causes may be the increasing use of biofuels in developed countries (see also food vs fuel), and an increasing demand for a more varied diet across the expanding middle-class populations of Asia.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] The FAO also raised concerns about the role of hedge funds speculating on prices leading to major shifts in prices.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] These factors, coupled with falling world-food stockpiles, all contributed to the worldwide rise in food prices.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Between 2006 and 2008 average world prices for rice rose by 217%, wheat by 136%, corn by 125% and soybeans by 107%.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] In late April 2008 rice prices hit 24 cents (US) per US pound, more than doubling the price in just seven months.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Although some commentators have argued that this food crisis stems from unprecedented global population growth, others point out that world population growth rates have dropped dramatically since the 1980s, and grain availability has continued to outpace population.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] To prevent price growth, food production should outpace population growth, which was about 1.2% per year.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] But there was a temporary drop in food production growth: for example, wheat production during 2006 and 2007 was 4% lower than that in 2004 and 2005.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] World population has grown from 1.6 billion in 1900 to over 7.5 billion today.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] The head of the International Food Policy Research Institute, stated in 2008 that the gradual change in diet among newly prosperous populations is the most important factor underpinning the rise in global food prices.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Where food consumption has increased, it has largely been in processed ("value added") foods, sold in developing and developed nations.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Total grain utilization growth since 2006 (up three percent, over the 2000–2006 per annum average of two percent) has been greatest in non-food usage, especially in feed and biofuels.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] One kilogram of beef requires seven kilograms of feed grain.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] These reports, therefore, conclude that usage in industrial, feed, and input intensive foods, not population growth among poor consumers of simple grains, has contributed to the price increases.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Rising meat consumption due to changes in lifestyle can in turn lead to higher energy consumption due to the higher energy-intensity of meat products, for example, one kilogram of meat uses about 19 times as much energy to produce it as the same amount of apple.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Although, the vast majority of the population in Asia remains rural and poor, the growth of the middle class in the region has been dramatic.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] For comparison, in 1990, the middle class grew by 9.7 percent in India and 8.6 percent in China, but by 2007 the growth rate was nearly 30 percent and 70 percent respectively.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] The corresponding increase in Asian affluence also brought with it a change in lifestyle and eating habits, particularly a demand for greater variety, leading to increased competition with western nations for already strained agricultural resources.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] This demand exacerbates dramatic increases in commodity prices such as oil.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Another issue with rising affluence in India and China was reducing the "shock absorber" of poor people who are forced to reduce their resource consumption when food prices rise.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] This reduced price elasticity and caused a sharp rise in food prices during some shortages.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] In the media, China is often mentioned as one of the main reasons for the increase in world food prices.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] However, China has to a large extent been able to meet its own demand for food, and even exports its surpluses in the world market.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Starting in 2007, the prices of fertilizers of all kinds increased dramatically, peaking around the summer of 2008 (see graphs by the International Fertilizer Industry Association).
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Prices approximately tripled for ammonia, urea, diammonium phosphate, muriate of potash (KCl -potassium chloride), and sulfuric acid (used for making phosphate fertilizer), and then fell just as dramatically in the latter part of 2008.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Some prices doubled within the six months before April 2008.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Part of the cause for these price rises was the rise in the price of oil, since most fertilizers require petroleum or natural gas to manufacture.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Although the main fossil fuel input for fertilizer comes from natural gas to generate hydrogen for the Haber–Bosch process (see: Ammonia production), natural gas has its own supply problems similar to those for oil.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Because natural gas can substitute for petroleum in some uses (for example, natural gas liquids and electricity generation), increasing prices for petroleum lead to increasing prices for natural gas, and thus for fertilizer.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Costs for fertilizer raw materials other than oil, such as potash, have been increasing as increased production of staples increases demand.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] This is causing a boom (with associated volatility) in agriculture stocks.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Unfortunately the IFPRI states that such shocks are likely to recur with several shocks in the future; compounded by a long history of neglecting agricultural investments.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] In the past, nations tended to keep more sizable food stockpiles, but more recently, due to a faster pace of food growth and ease of importation, less emphasis is placed on high stockpiles.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] For example, in February 2008 wheat stockpiles hit a 60-year low in the United States (see also 2008 global rice crisis).
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Stocks are often calculated as a residual between production and consumption, but it becomes difficult to discriminate between a de-stocking policy choices of individual countries and a deficit between production and consumption.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Destabilizing influences, including indiscriminate lending and real estate speculation, led to a crisis in January 2008 and eroded investment in food commodities.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Foreign investment drives productivity improvements, and other gains for farmers.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Goldman Sachs' entry into the commodities market via the Goldman Sachs Commodity Index has been implicated by some in the 2007–2008 world food price crisis.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] In a 2010 article in Harper's magazine, Frederick Kaufman accused Goldman Sachs of profiting while many people went hungry or even starved.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] He argued that Goldman's large purchases of long-options on wheat futures created a demand shock in the wheat market, which disturbed the normal relationship between supply and demand and price levels.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] For example, the report points out that even commodities without futures markets also saw price rises during the period.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] In opening developing countries to developed world food imports subsidised by Western governments, developing nations can become more dependent upon food imports if local agriculture does not improve.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] While developed countries pressured the developing world to abolish subsidies in the interest of trade liberalization, rich countries largely kept subsidies in place for their own farmers.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] United States government subsidies for 2008 pushed production toward biofuel rather than food.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] One systemic cause for the price rise is held to be the diversion of food crops (maize in particular) for making first-generation biofuels.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] An estimated 100 million tons of grain per year are being redirected from food to fuel.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] (Total worldwide grain production for 2007 was just over 2000 million tons.) As farmers devoted larger parts of their crops to fuel production than in previous years, land and resources available for food production were reduced correspondingly.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] This has resulted in less food available for human consumption, especially in developing and least developed countries, where a family's daily allowances for food purchases are extremely limited.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] The crisis can be seen, in a sense, to dichotomize rich and poor nations, since, for example, filling a tank of an average car with biofuel, amounts to as much maize (Africa's principal food staple) as an African person consumes in an entire year.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Brazil, the world's second largest producer of ethanol after the US, is considered to have the world's first sustainable biofuels economy and its government claims Brazil's sugar cane based ethanol industry has not contributed to the 2008 food crises.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] An economic assessment published in July 2008 by the OECD disagrees with the World Bank report regarding the negative effects of subsidies and trade restrictions, finding that the effect of biofuels on food prices are much smaller.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] The report discusses some existing problems and potential risks and asks the Brazilian government for caution to avoid jeopardizing its environmental and social sustainability.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] German Chancellor Angela Merkel said the rise in food prices is due to poor agricultural policies and changing eating habits in developing nations, not biofuels as some critics claim.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] On 29 April 2008, US President George W.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Bush declared during a press conference that "85 percent of the world's food prices are caused by weather, increased demand and energy prices", and recognized that "15 percent has been caused by ethanol".
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] On 4 July 2008, *The Guardian* reported that a leaked World Bank report estimated the rise in food prices caused by biofuels to be 75%.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] This report was officially released in July 2008.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Since reaching record high prices in June 2008, corn prices fell 50% by October 2008, declining sharply together with other commodities, including oil.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] As ethanol production from corn has continued at the same levels, some have argued this trend shows the belief that the increased demand for corn to produce ethanol was mistaken.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] "Analysts, including some in the ethanol sector, say ethanol demand adds about 75 cents to $1.00 per bushel to the price of corn, as a rule of thumb.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Other analysts say it adds around 20 percent, or just under 80 cents per bushel at current prices.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] The World Bank lists the effect of biofuels as an important contributor to higher food prices.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] According to the United States Department of Agriculture (USDA), global wheat imports and stocks have decreased, domestic consumption has stagnated, and world wheat production has decreased from 2006 to 2008.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] In the United States, government subsidies for ethanol production have prompted many farmers to switch to production for biofuel.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Maize is the primary crop used for the production of ethanol, with the United States being the biggest producer of maize ethanol.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] As a result, 23 percent of United States maize crops were being used for ethanol in 2006–2007 (up from 6 percent in 2005–2006), and the USDA expects the United States to use 81 million tons of maize for ethanol production in the 2007–2008 season, up 37 percent.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] This not only diverts grains from food, but it diverts agricultural land from food production.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Nevertheless, supporters of ethanol claim that using corn for ethanol is not responsible for the worst food riots in the world, many of which have been caused by the price of rice and oil, which are not affected by biofuel use but rather by supply and demand.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] However, a World Bank policy research working paper released in July 2008 says that biofuels have raised food prices between 70 and 75 percent.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] The study found that higher oil prices and a weak dollar explain 25–30% of total price rise.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] The paper concludes that increased production of biofuels in the US and EU were supported by subsidies and tariffs on imports, and considers that without these policies, price increases would have been smaller.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] The Renewable Fuel Association (RFA) published a rebuttal based on the version leaked before the formal release of the World Bank's paper.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] The RFA critique considers that the analysis is highly subjective and that the author "estimates the effect of global food prices from the weak dollar and the direct and indirect effect of high petroleum prices and attributes everything else to biofuels".
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] An economic assessment report also published in July 2008 by the OECD agrees with the World Bank report regarding the negative effects of subsidies and trade restrictions, but found that the effect of biofuels on food prices are much smaller.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] The assessment calls on governments for more open markets in biofuels and feedstocks to improve efficiency and lower costs.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] According to the *New York Times* on 9 April 2008, the United States government pays farmers to idle their cropland under a conservation program.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] This policy reached a peak of 36,800,000 acres (149,000 km2) idled in 2007, that is 8% of cropland in United States, representing a total area bigger than the state of New York.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] The global food crisis has renewed calls for removal of distorting agricultural subsidies in developed countries.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Support to farmers in OECD countries totals US$280 billion annually, which compares to official development assistance of just US$80 billion in 2004, and farm support depresses global food prices, according to OECD estimates.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] These agricultural subsidies lead to underdevelopment in rural developing countries, including the least developed countries; meanwhile subsidised food increases overconsumption in developed countries.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] The US Farm Bill brought in by the Bush Administration in 2002 increased agricultural subsidies by 80% and cost the US taxpayer US$190 billion.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] In 2003, the EU agreed to extend the Common Agricultural Policy until 2013.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Former UNDP Administrator Malloch Brown renewed calls for reform of the farm subsidies such as the CAP.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Japan is forced to import more than 767,000 tons of rice annually from the United States, Thailand, and other countries due to WTO rules.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Japan is not allowed to re-export this rice to other countries without approval.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] This rice is generally left to rot and then used for animal feed.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Under pressure, the United States and Japan are poised to strike a deal to remove such restrictions.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] It is expected 1.5 million tons of high-grade American rice will enter the market soon.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Several distinct weather- and climate-related incidents have caused disruptions in crop production.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Perhaps the most influential is the extended drought in Australia, in particular the fertile Murray-Darling Basin, which produces large amounts of wheat and rice.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] The drought has caused the annual rice harvest to fall by as much as 98% from pre-drought levels.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Australia is historically the second-largest exporter of wheat after the United States, producing up to 25 million tons in a good year, the vast majority for export.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] However, the 2006 harvest was 9.8 million.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Other events that have negatively affected the price of food include the 2006 heat wave in California's San Joaquin Valley, which killed large numbers of farm animals, and unseasonable 2008 rains in Kerala, India, which destroyed swathes of grain.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] These incidents are consistent with the effects of climate change.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] The effects of Cyclone Nargis on Burma in May 2008 caused a spike in the price of rice.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Burma has historically been a rice exporter, though yields have fallen as government price controls have reduced incentives for farmers.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] The storm surge inundated rice paddies up to 30 miles (48 km) inland in the Irrawaddy Delta, raising concern that the salt could make the fields infertile.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] The FAO had previously estimated that Burma would export up to 600,000 tons of rice in 2008, but concerns were raised in the cyclone's aftermath that Burma may be forced to import rice for the first time, putting further upward pressure on global rice prices.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Stem rust reappeared in 1998 in Uganda (and possibly earlier in Kenya) with the particularly virulent UG99 fungus.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Unlike other rusts, which only partially affect crop yields, UG99 can bring 100% crop loss.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Up to 80% yield losses were recently recorded in Kenya.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] As of 2005 stem rust was still believed to be "largely under control worldwide except in Eastern Africa".
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] But by January 2007 an even more virulent strain had gone across the Red Sea into Yemen.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] FAO first reported on 5 March 2008 that Ug99 had now spread to major wheat-growing areas in Iran.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] These countries in North Africa and Middle East consume over 150% of their own wheat production; the failure of this staple crop thus adds a major burden on them.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] The disease is now expected to spread over China and the Far-East.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Sundquist points out that large areas of croplands are lost year after year, due mainly to soil erosion, water depletion and urbanisation.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] According to him "60,000 km2/year of land becomes so severely degraded that it loses its productive capacity and becomes wasteland", and even more are affected to a lesser extent, adding to the crop supply problem.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Additionally, agricultural production is also lost due to water depletion.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Northern China in particular has depleted much of its non-renewables aquifers, which now impacts negatively its crop production.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Urbanisation is another, smaller, difficult to estimate cause of annual cropland reduction.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] One possible environmental factor in the food price crisis is rising background levels of ground-level tropospheric ozone in the atmosphere.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Plants have been shown to have a high sensitivity to ozone levels, and lower yields of important food crops, such as wheat and soybeans, may have been a result of elevated ozone levels.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Ozone levels in the Yangtze Delta were studied for their effect on oilseed rape, a member of the cabbage family that produces one-third of the vegetable oil used in China.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Plants grown in chambers that controlled ozone levels exhibited a 10–20 percent reduction in size and weight (biomass) when exposed to elevated ozone levels.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Production of seeds and oil was also reduced.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] The Chinese authors of this study also reported that rice grown in chambers that controlled ozone levels exhibited a 14 to 20 percent reduction in biomass yield when exposed to ozone levels over 25 times higher than was normal for the region.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] From the beginning of 2007 to early 2008, the prices of some of the most basic international food commodities increased dramatically on international markets.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] The international market price of wheat doubled from February 2007 to February 2008 hitting a record high of over US$10 a bushel.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Rice prices also reached ten-year highs.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] In some nations, milk and meat prices more than doubled, while soy (which hit a 34-year high price in December 2007) and maize prices have increased dramatically.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Total food import bills rose by an estimated 25% for developing countries in 2007.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Researchers from the Overseas Development Institute have suggested this problem will be worsened by a likely fall in food aid.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] As food aid is programmed by budget rather than volume, rising food prices mean that the World Food Programme (WFP) needs an extra $500 million just to sustain the current operations.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] To ensure that food remains available for their domestic populations and to combat dramatic price inflation, major rice exporters, such as China, Brazil, India, Indonesia, Vietnam, Cambodia and Egypt, imposed strict export bans on rice.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Conversely, several other nations, including Argentina, Ukraine, Russia, and Serbia either imposed high tariffs or blocked the export of wheat and other foodstuffs altogether, driving up prices still further for net food importing nations while trying to isolate their internal markets.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] North Korea suffered from the food crisis to such extent that a North Korean official was quoted in June '08 with saying "Life is more than difficult.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] It seems that everyone is going to die".
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] This nation however is solely relying on food assistance to cope with the crisis.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] A May 2008 national survey found that food banks and pantries across the US were being forced to cut back on food distribution as 99 percent of respondents reported an increase in the number of people requesting services.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Rising food and fuel prices, inadequate food stamp benefits, unemployment, underemployment, and rent or mortgage costs were factors reported as forcing an average of 15–20 percent more people.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Compounding this issue, USDA bonus foods have declined by $200 million and local food donations were down nationally about 9 percent over the same period.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] According to the California Association of Food Banks, which is an umbrella organization of nearly all food banks in the state, food banks are at the "beginning of a crisis".
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] If global price movements are transmitted to local markets, farmers in the developing world could benefit from the rising price of food.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] According to researchers from the Overseas Development Institute, this may depend on farmers' capacity to respond to changing market conditions.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Experience suggests that farmers lack the credit and inputs needed to respond in the short term.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] In the medium or long term, however, they could benefit, as seen in the Asian Green Revolution or in many African countries in the recent past.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] As grain prices increased, China's numerous small-holding milk farmers, as well as producers of feed for cattle, were unable to exist economically.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] As a result, they turned to putting additives into the feed and milk, including melamine, to boost the measured level of protein.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Hundreds of thousands of children became ill, China's milk exports virtually ended, executives and officials were arrested and some executed, and companies went bankrupt.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] The price rises affected parts of Asia and Africa particularly severely with Burkina Faso, Cameroon, Senegal, Mauritania, Côte d'Ivoire, Egypt and Morocco seeing protests and riots in late 2007 and early 2008 over the unavailability of basic food staples.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Other countries that have seen food riots or are facing related unrest are: Mexico, Bolivia, Yemen, Uzbekistan, Bangladesh, Pakistan, Sri Lanka, and South Africa.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Popular protests plagued Gafsa and other rural towns in the country of Tunisia in 2008 against the deaths of two miners and high unemployment rates in the government.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Anti-government riots were suppressed and two people died.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Unemployed demonstrators and food shortages protests erupted in towns near Gafsa in inspiration but was suppressed harshly.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] A popular movement unfolded as a series of violent at times but nonviolent demonstrations and events throughout Morocco in 2007–2008 after strikes took place.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Unfortunately, during riots in Sidi Ifni, 10 demonstrators died after police cursed the protests in June 2008.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] In November–December, a wave of strikes and protests and violence hit the country as scattered protests broke out against food prices and shortages.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] The movement was quelled violently with a swift response by the authorities.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] 10,000 workers rioted close to the Bangladeshi capital Dhaka, smashing cars and buses and vandalising factories in anger at high food prices and low wages.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Dozens of people, including at least 20 police officials, were injured in the violence.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Ironically, the country achieved food self-sufficiency in 2002, but food prices increased drastically due to the reliance of agriculture on oil and fossil fuels.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Economists estimate 30 million of the country's 150 million people could go hungry.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] In April 2008, the Brazilian government announced a temporary ban on the export of rice.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] The ban was intended to protect domestic consumers.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] One of the earlier food riots took place in Burkina Faso, on 22 February, when rioting broke out in the country's second and third largest cities over soaring food prices (up to a 65 percent increase), sparing the capital, Ouagadougou, where soldiers were mobilized throughout strategic points.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] The government promised to lower taxes on food and to release food stocks.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Over 100 people were arrested in one of the towns.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] A ban was also imposed on exportation of cereals.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Cameroon, the world's fourth largest cocoa producer, saw large scale rioting in late February 2008 in Douala, the country's commercial capital.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Protesters were against inflating food and fuel prices, as well as the attempt by President Paul Biya to extend his 25-year rule.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Protesters set up barricades, burned tires, and targeted businesses that they believed belonged to the Biya family, high members of the ruling party, the government, or France.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] It became the first protest in the nation's history in which minute- by-minute events were covered by social media.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] By 27 February, a strike was taking place in thirty-one cities, including Yaoundé, Douala, Bamenda, Bafoussam, Buea, Limbe, Tiko, Muea, Mutengene, and Kumba.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] At least seven people were killed in the worst unrest seen in the country in over fifteen years.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Youths were mobilized in ways that had not been seen since the days of the villes mortes.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Part of the government response to the protests was a reduction in import taxes on foods including rice, flour, and fish.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] The government reached an agreement with retailers by which prices would be lowered in exchange for the reduced import taxes.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] As of late April 2008, however, reports suggested that prices had not eased and in some cases had even increased.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] On 24 April 2008, the government of Cameroon announced a two-year emergency program designed to double Cameroon's food production and achieve food self-sufficiency.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] On 31 March, Côte d'Ivoire's capital Abidjan saw police use tear gas and a dozen protesters injured following food riots that gripped the city.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] The riots followed dramatic hikes in the price of food and fuel, with the price of beef rising from US$1.68 to $2.16 per kilogram, and the price of gasoline rising from $1.44 to $2.04 per liter, in only three days.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] In Egypt, a boy was killed from a gunshot to the head after Egyptian police intervened in violent demonstrations over rising food prices that gripped the industrial city of Mahalla on 8 April 2008.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Large swathes of the population have been hit as food prices, and particularly the price of bread, have doubled over the last several months as a result of producers exploiting a shortage that has existed since 2006.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Drought and the food price crisis threatened thousands in Ethiopia.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] On 12 April 2008, the Haitian Senate voted to dismiss Prime Minister Jacques-Édouard Alexis after violent food riots hit the country.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] The food riots caused the death of five people.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Prices for food items such as rice, beans, fruit and condensed milk have gone up 50 percent in Haiti since late 2007 while the price of fuel has tripled in only two months.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Riots broke out in April due to the high prices, and the government had been attempting to restore order by subsidizing a 15 percent reduction in the price of rice.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] India exports two kinds of rice: common and higher quality basmati.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] In October 2007, the country imposed a minimum export price on common rice in order to increase domestic stocks by reducing exports.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] In December 2007, they had raised the price, but exports had not declined.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Consequently, in March 2008, the government banned the export of common rice.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] In response to criticism from some rice-importing countries, India made exceptions to allow exports to neighbors Bangladesh and Bhutan and some low-income African countries, but a limited amount was actually exported.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] The export ban was lifted in September 2011.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Street protests over the price of food took place in Indonesia where food staples and gasoline have nearly doubled in price since January 2008.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] In April 2008, the Latin American members of the United Nations' FAO met in Brasília to confront the issues of high food prices, scarcities and violence that affect the region.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] The president of Mexico, Felipe Calderón, with industry representatives and members of the Confederation of Industrial Chambers (Concamin), agreed to freeze prices of more than 150 consumer staples, such as coffee, sardines, tuna, oil, soup or tea, among others, until the end of December 2008.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] The measure was carried out in an attempt to control inflation, which stood at an annual rate of 4.95%, the highest increase since December 2004.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Mexican baking company Grupo Bimbo's CEO, Daniel Servitje, announced in the 19th Plenary Meeting of the Mexico–China Business Committee that Bimbo agreed to freeze their product prices, despite a 20% rise in production costs.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Bimbo is one of the most important baking companies worldwide, having recently expanded to China.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Bimbo has also acquired five bakeries in the United States and Canada.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] In mid February, rioting that started in the Mozambican rural town of Chokwe and then spread to the capital, Maputo, has resulted in at least four deaths.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] The riots were reported in the media to have been, at least in part, over food prices and were termed "food riots".
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] A biofuel advocacy publication, however, claimed that these were, in fact, "fuel riots", limited to the rise in the cost of diesel, and argued that the "food riot" characterization worked to fan "anti-biofuels sentiment".
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] The Pakistan Army has been deployed to avoid the seizure of food from fields and warehouses.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] This hasn't stopped the food prices from increasing.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] The new government has been blamed for not managing the countries food stockpiles properly.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Once the world's top rice producer, has produced enough rice to feed itself until now.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Rice exports dropped over four decades from nearly 4 million tons to only about 40,000 tons last year, mostly due to neglect by Myanmar's ruling generals of infrastructure, including irrigation and warehousing.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] On 3 May 2008 Cyclone Nargis stripped Myanmar's rice-growing districts, ruining large areas with salt water.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Food and Agriculture Organization estimates that these areas produce 65 percent of Myanmar's rice.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Worries of long-term food shortages and rationing are rife.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] The military regime says nothing about the rice crisis, but continues to export rice at the same rate.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] "...at least the next two harvests are going to be greatly affected and there'll be virtually no output from those areas during that time.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] So we're likely to see considerable food and rice shortages for the next couple of years.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] The damage to the economy is going to be profound." said economist and Myanmar expert Sean Turnell, of Australia's Macquarie University.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] On 22 February 2007, a small group of individuals protested the current state of consumer prices in the country.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] On 15 August 2007 the government removed subsidies on fuel causing a rapid and unannounced increase in prices.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Protests grew into what became known as the *Saffron Revolution*.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] In Panama, in response to higher rice prices the government began buying rice at the high market price and selling rice to the public at a lower subsidized price at food kiosks.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] In the Philippines, the Arroyo government insisted on 13 April that there would be no food riots in the country and that there could be no comparison with Haiti's situation.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Chief Presidential Legal Counsel, Sergio Apostol stated that: "Haiti is not trying to solve the problem, while we are doing something to address the issue.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] So, no comparison..." Comments by the Justice Secretary, Raul Gonzalez, the following day, that food riots are not far fetched, were quickly rebuked by the rest of the government.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] On 15 April, the Philippines, the world's largest rice importer, urged China, Japan, and other key Asian nations, to convene an emergency meeting, especially taking issue with those countries' rice export bans.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] "Free trade should be flowing", Philippine Agriculture Secretary Arthur Yap stated.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] In late April 2008, the Philippines government requested that the World Bank exert pressure on rice exporting countries to end export restrictions.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] The Russian government pressured retailers to freeze food prices before key elections for fear of a public backlash against the rising cost of food in October 2007.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] On 31 March 2008, Senegal had riots in response to the rise in the price of food and fuel.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Twenty-four people were arrested and detained in a response that one local human rights group claimed included "torture" and other "unspeakable acts" on the part of the security forces.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Further protests took place in Dakar on 26 April 2008.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Riots in Somalia occurred on 5 May 2008 over the price of food, in which five protesters were killed.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] The protests occurred amid a serious humanitarian emergency due to the Ethiopian war in Somalia.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] In 2008, *The Christian Science Monitor*, neweurasia, and other media observers predicted that a nascent hunger crisis would erupt into a full famine as a consequence of energy shortages at the time.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] UN experts announced on 10 October that almost one-third of Tajikistan's 6.7 million inhabitants were at risk of running out of food during the winter of 2008–09.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Food riots in southern Yemen that began in late March and continued through early April, saw police stations torched, and roadblocks were set up by armed protesters.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] The army has deployed tanks and other military vehicles.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Although the riots involved thousands of demonstrators over several days and over 100 arrests, officials claimed no fatalities; residents, however, claimed that at least one of the fourteen wounded people has died.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] The FAO released a study in December 2007 projecting a 49 percent increase in African cereal prices, and 53 percent in European prices, through July 2008.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] In April 2008, the World Bank, in combination with the International Monetary Fund, announced a series of measures aimed at mitigating the crisis, including increased loans to African farmers and emergency monetary aid to badly affected areas such as Haiti.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] According to FAO director Jacques Diouf, however, the World Food Programme needed an immediate cash injection of at least $1700 million, far more than the tens of million-worth in measures already pledged.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] 2013 research concluded that the spike was the result of an unusual combination of circumstances and prices in the future will be higher than before the spike, depending on oil prices, climate change, and future diets.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] WDM noted in 2010 that after the spike in prices in 2008, prices of wheat, maize and rice lowered but were still higher than before the crisis.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] The impacts of the spike on poor people were concentrated in low-income countries and may have been less severe than once thought, thanks to rising rural wages in some countries.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] The researchers called on developing countries to ensure good data on the key indicators of distress and to strengthen social protection, and on those involved in international development to continue increasing focus on reducing child malnutrition and stimulating agricultural development.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] IFAD is making up to US$200 million available to support poor farmers boost food production in face of the global food crisis.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Bush said he was asking Congress to approve an extra $770 million funding for international food aid.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] On 16 October 2008, in a speech at a United Nations gathering on World Food Day, former US president Bill Clinton criticized the bipartisan coalition in Congress that blocked efforts to make some aid donations in cash rather than in food.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] The release of Japan's rice reserves onto the market may bring the rice price down significantly.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] As of 16 May, anticipation of the move had already lowered prices by 14% in a single week.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] On 30 April 2008, Thailand announced an agreement in principle to create the Organization of Rice Exporting Countries (OREC) with the potential to develop a price-fixing cartel for rice.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] In June 2008 the FAO hosted a High-Level Conference on World Food Security, in which $1.2 billion in food aid was committed for the 75 million people in 60 countries hardest hit by rising food prices.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] In June 2008, a sustained commitment from the G8 was called for by some humanitarian organizations.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] In December 2008, the global economic slowdown, decreasing oil prices, and speculation of decreased demand for commodities worldwide brought about sharp decreases in the price of staple crops from their earlier highs.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Corn prices on the Chicago Board of Trade dropped from US$7.99 per bushel in June to US$3.74 per bushel in mid-December; wheat and rice prices experienced similar decreases.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] The UN's Food and Agriculture Organization, however, warned against "a false sense of security", noting that the credit crisis could cause farmers to reduce plantings.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] FAO convened a World Summit on Food Security at its headquarters in Rome in November 2008, noting that food prices remained high in developing countries and that the global food security situation has worsened.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] By early 2010, food prices had risen again to surpass the record highs of 2008.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Some commentators saw this as the resumption of the price spike seen in 2007–08.
[src:chrysler/2007-2008-world-food-price-crisis] Prices had dropped after good weather helped increase grain yields while demand had dropped due to the recession.
[src:chrysler/2008-central-asia-energy-crisis] The **2008 Central Asia energy crisis** was an energy shortage in Central Asia, which, combined with the severe weather of the 2007-08 winter (the coldest since 1969) and high prices for food and fuel, caused considerable hardship for many.
[src:chrysler/2008-central-asia-energy-crisis] The abnormally cold weather pushed demand up for electricity, exacerbating the crisis.
[src:chrysler/2008-central-asia-energy-crisis] The situation was most dire in Tajikistan.
[src:chrysler/2008-central-asia-energy-crisis] An international appeal was made by the United Nations, NGOs, and the Red Cross and Red Crescent for around US$25 million to assist the government.
[src:chrysler/2008-central-asia-energy-crisis] At the time, The UN warned that millions face starvation during the 2008-09 winter.
[src:chrysler/2008-central-asia-energy-crisis] In April 2008, Pradeep Mitra, World Bank chief economist for Europe and Central Asia, issued an uncharacteristic statement, urging the worse-hit countries to spend more on social assistance and "top up" their social programs.
[src:chrysler/2008-central-asia-energy-crisis] Starting on January 13, 2008, many villages received only one to three hours of electricity per day, and the capital Dushanbe cut power to residential areas overnight.
[src:chrysler/2008-central-asia-energy-crisis] On January 26, 2008, Dushanbe cut power to places of entertainment (including restaurants, shops, pharmacies, markets, and public bathhouses), causing many to close until spring.
[src:chrysler/2008-central-asia-energy-crisis] There were only few visible lights in the city which were from the owners of generators, factories, or people who had illegally tapped the power lines.
[src:chrysler/2008-central-asia-energy-crisis] The restriction was set to end February 10, however it was subsequently extended.
[src:chrysler/2008-central-asia-energy-crisis] There were only few exemptions to the restrictions which included government offices, hospitals, and certain industrial cities, such as Tursunzoda, which had a large aluminium plant.
[src:chrysler/2008-central-asia-energy-crisis] Because of inoperable central heating systems in Dushanbe and other cities, residents in apartment blocks had no means other than electricity to heat their homes.
[src:chrysler/2008-central-asia-energy-crisis] The situation was exacerbated by the cold winter, with temperatures reaching -20 degrees Celsius.
[src:chrysler/2008-central-asia-energy-crisis] Dushanbe residents reported wearing several jackets and overcoats to sleep and all family members sleeping under a single blanket to share warmth.
[src:chrysler/2008-central-asia-energy-crisis] The UN's World Food Programme also declared the food situation as being in emergency shortage, in both cities and rural areas.
[src:chrysler/2008-central-asia-energy-crisis] As of mid-January 2008, the state-run media did not discuss the problem.
[src:chrysler/2008-central-asia-energy-crisis] Subsequently, throughout the month of February, there emerged numerous Western media reports of children dying in maternity wards of hospitals during blackouts.
[src:chrysler/2008-central-asia-energy-crisis] The Tajik government maintains that the blackouts were not responsible for any deaths.
[src:chrysler/2008-central-asia-energy-crisis] The Tajik government has appealed for international aid.
[src:chrysler/2008-central-asia-energy-crisis] Meanwhile, aid workers and diplomats urged the government to declare a state of emergency.
[src:chrysler/2008-central-asia-energy-crisis] The handling of the crisis has raised questions about the competence of the political leadership.
[src:chrysler/2008-central-asia-energy-crisis] UN experts announced on 10 October that almost one-third of Tajikistan's 6.7 million inhabitants did not have enough to eat for the winter of 2008–09.
[src:chrysler/2008-central-asia-energy-crisis] In Kyrgyzstan, also rich in hydroelectric resources, the cold weather had made demand 10% higher than in the winter of 2006/2007, which depleted the main Toktogul reservoir for hydroelectric power.
[src:chrysler/2008-central-asia-energy-crisis] Beginning in late December 2007, the unusually harsh weather had frozen the gas supply to numerous homes and businesses across Uzbekistan.
[src:chrysler/2008-central-asia-energy-crisis] As a result, there had been numerous demonstrations and protests against the government, in favor of an insured uninterrupted supply of gas and electricity.
[src:chrysler/2008-central-asia-energy-crisis] The government response was varied, and in Karakalpakstan, they met protesters and promised to rectify the situation, while the local government head of Hazarasp responded to a complaint by one woman by cutting off gas altogether to all the houses on her street.
[src:chrysler/2008-central-asia-energy-crisis] Some in Uzbekistan were able to turn to "traditional methods" for heating, and it was reported that some villages which had no trees left because villagers have cut them down to heat their homes and cook food.
[src:chrysler/2008-central-asia-energy-crisis] This had an expected negative effect on the economy, because the leaves are essential to the local silk industry, and the fruit grown on these trees are the main source of income for many villagers.
[src:chrysler/2008-central-asia-energy-crisis] In some provinces of Turkmenistan, villagers were burning saxaul plants, a traditional Turkmen way to heat homes, since in the cities, the central heating pipes have been neglected and failed to produce adequate heat.
[src:chrysler/2008-european-union-stimulus-plan] On 26 November 2008, the European Commission proposed a **European stimulus plan** (also referred to as the **European Economic Recovery Plan**) amounting to 200 billion euros to cope with Great Recession in Europe and the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:chrysler/2008-european-union-stimulus-plan] It aimed at limiting the effects of the Great Recession through national economic policies, with measures extended over a period of two years.
[src:chrysler/2008-european-union-stimulus-plan] The European Commission published a plan on 26 November 2008 responding to the current economic crisis in the 27 member countries of the Union.
[src:chrysler/2008-european-union-stimulus-plan] The plan combined short-term measures to stimulate demand and maintain jobs and longer-term measures to invest in strategic sectors, including research and innovation.
[src:chrysler/2008-european-union-stimulus-plan] The aim was to promote growth and ensure sustainable prosperity.
[src:chrysler/2008-european-union-stimulus-plan] The plan included targeted and temporary measures amounting to 200 billion euros, or 1.5% of EU GDP, using both the national budgets of the national governments, the budget of the EU and that of the European Investment Bank.
[src:chrysler/2008-european-union-stimulus-plan] The plan also built on the Small Business Act for Europe, published earlier in June 2008, which was concerned with supporting the small business sector within the European Union.
[src:chrysler/2008-european-union-stimulus-plan] The plan included a broad range of actions at the national level and at EU level to help households and industrial firms (particularly automobile and construction).
[src:chrysler/2008-european-union-stimulus-plan] On implementation, the Commission requested member state leaders meeting at the European Council on 11-12 December 2008 to endorse the plan.
[src:chrysler/2008-european-union-stimulus-plan] National plans are often close to 1.2 percentage points of GDP, as recommended by the European Commission, and are focused on 2008 and 2009.
[src:chrysler/2008-european-union-stimulus-plan] However, Germany and Spain have announced fiscal stimulus of respectively 3.3% (two plans altogether) and 8.1% of their GDP.
[src:chrysler/2008-european-union-stimulus-plan] The plan announced by the European Commission at the end of November recommended measures to revive the economy but did not specify much the nature of the plans.
[src:chrysler/2008-european-union-stimulus-plan] Some plans are focused on the stimulation of demand (United Kingdom, to a lesser extent Spain, Italy or the second German plan), other plans insist more in incentives to supply (French plan, first German plan ).
[src:chrysler/2008-european-union-stimulus-plan] Measures took on expenditure to improve demand generally include measures to support medium-term growth through increased public spending on infrastructures (road networks and railway) and aids to the housing sector (notably construction and renovation).
[src:chrysler/2008-european-union-stimulus-plan] Several countries have also announced short-term measures to relieve the effects of the crisis on the poorest people (increase in benefits and allowances to households with low incomes and unemployed).
[src:chrysler/2008-european-union-stimulus-plan] However, these aids have often limited effects on the economy, because their amounts are insignificant.
[src:chrysler/2008-european-union-stimulus-plan] Other measures affected national taxation systems.
[src:chrysler/2008-european-union-stimulus-plan] The UK was the only country that opted for a temporary decline in the standard VAT rate, by 2.5 percentage points.
[src:chrysler/2008-european-union-stimulus-plan] In Germany, employer contributions were lowered.
[src:chrysler/2008-european-union-stimulus-plan] Most plans include incentive measures to SMEs and development of green energy.
[src:chrysler/2008-société-générale-trading-loss] In January 2008, the bank Société Générale lost approximately €4.9 billion closing out positions over three days of trading beginning January 21, 2008, a period in which the market was experiencing a large drop in equity indices.
[src:chrysler/2008-société-générale-trading-loss] The bank states these positions were fraudulent transactions created by Jérôme Kerviel, a trader with the company.
[src:chrysler/2008-société-générale-trading-loss] The police stated they lacked evidence to charge him with fraud and charged him with breach of trust and illegally accessing computers.
[src:chrysler/2008-société-générale-trading-loss] Kerviel states his actions were known to his superiors and that the losses were caused by panic selling by the bank.
[src:chrysler/2008-société-générale-trading-loss] Société Générale's own wrongs were later established by a French jurisdiction, which led the Cour de cassation to cancel the €4.9 billion sanction on Kerviel.
[src:chrysler/2008-société-générale-trading-loss] Kerviel joined the middle offices in the bank Société Générale in the summer of 2000, working in its compliance department.
[src:chrysler/2008-société-générale-trading-loss] In 2005 he was promoted to the bank's Delta One products team in Paris where he was a junior trader.
[src:chrysler/2008-société-générale-trading-loss] Société Générale's Delta One business includes program trading, exchange-traded funds (ETFs), swaps, index and quantitative trading.
[src:chrysler/2008-société-générale-trading-loss] Bank officials claim that Kerviel tried to conceal the activity by creating losing trades intentionally so as to offset his early gains.
[src:chrysler/2008-société-générale-trading-loss] According to the BBC, Kerviel generated €1.4 billion in hidden profits by the end of 2007.
[src:chrysler/2008-société-générale-trading-loss] His employers say they uncovered unauthorized trading traced to Kerviel on January 19, 2008.
[src:chrysler/2008-société-générale-trading-loss] The bank then closed out these positions over three days of trading beginning January 21, 2008, a period in which the market was experiencing a large drop in equity indices, and losses attributed are estimated at €4.9 billion.
[src:chrysler/2008-société-générale-trading-loss] The bank claimed Kerviel "had taken massive fraudulent directional positions in 2007 and 2008 far beyond his limited authority" and that the trades involved European stock index futures.
[src:chrysler/2008-société-générale-trading-loss] Though bank officials say Kerviel apparently worked alone, skeptics question how unauthorized trading of this magnitude could go unnoticed.
[src:chrysler/2008-société-générale-trading-loss] Kerviel's unassuming background and position have heightened the skepticism that he worked alone.
[src:chrysler/2008-société-générale-trading-loss] Some analysts suggest that unauthorized trading of this scale may have gone unnoticed initially due to the high volume in low-risk trades normally conducted by his department.
[src:chrysler/2008-société-générale-trading-loss] The bank said that whenever the fake trades were questioned, Kerviel would describe it as a mistake then cancel the trade followed by replacing that trade with another transaction using a different instrument to avoid detection.
[src:chrysler/2008-société-générale-trading-loss] Kerviel is not thought to have profited personally from the suspicious trades.
[src:chrysler/2008-société-générale-trading-loss] Prosecutors say Kerviel has been cooperative with the investigation, and has told them his actions were also practiced by other traders in the company.
[src:chrysler/2008-société-générale-trading-loss] Kerviel admits to exceeding his credit limits, but claims he was working to increase bank profits.
[src:chrysler/2008-société-générale-trading-loss] He told authorities that the bank was happy with his previous year's performance, and was expecting to be paid a €300,000 bonus.
[src:chrysler/2008-société-générale-trading-loss] Family members speaking out say the bank is using Kerviel as a scapegoat to excuse its recent heavy losses.
[src:chrysler/2008-société-générale-trading-loss] The bank states that Kerviel was assigned to arbitrage discrepancies between equity derivatives and cash equity prices, and "began creating the fictitious trades in late 2006 and early 2007, but that these transactions were relatively small.
[src:chrysler/2008-société-générale-trading-loss] The fake trading increased in frequency, and in size".
[src:chrysler/2008-société-générale-trading-loss] The Executive Chairman of Société Générale, Daniel Bouton described the pattern as like "a mutating virus" in which hundreds of thousands of trades were hidden behind offsetting faked hedge trades.
[src:chrysler/2008-société-générale-trading-loss] Officials say Kerviel was careful to close the trades in just two or three days, just before the trades' timed controls would trigger notice from the bank's internal control system, and Kerviel would then shift those older positions to newly initiated trades.
[src:chrysler/2008-société-générale-trading-loss] City experts have expressed skepticism of the bank's account, saying that a pattern of closing out trades within the three-day cycle alleged could not be accomplished given the immense sums involved.
[src:chrysler/2008-société-générale-trading-loss] In answers to the rumors alleging Jérôme Kerviel had fled Paris following the discovery of the unauthorized trading, on January 24, 2008, Kerviel's lawyer denied that he attempted to disappear and said he remained in Paris to face the accusations.
[src:chrysler/2008-société-générale-trading-loss] Also on January 24, 2008, Société Générale filed a lawsuit against "a 31-year-old person" for creating fraudulent documents, using forged documents and making attacks on an automated system, according to Clarisse Grillon, a spokeswoman for the Nanterre prosecutor.
[src:chrysler/2008-société-générale-trading-loss] *Le Figaro* reported that in addition to the Société Générale lawsuit, a group of shareholders filed a lawsuit for fraud, breach of trust and forgery.
[src:chrysler/2008-société-générale-trading-loss] On the eve and afternoon of January 25, 2008, police raided the Paris headquarters of Société Générale and Kerviel's apartment in the western suburb of Neuilly-sur-Seine to seize his computer files.
[src:chrysler/2008-société-générale-trading-loss] On January 26, 2008, the Paris prosecutors' office stated that Kerviel "is not on the run.
[src:chrysler/2008-société-générale-trading-loss] He will be questioned at the appropriate time, as soon as the police have analysed documents provided by Société Générale." He was taken into police custody later that day.
[src:chrysler/2008-société-générale-trading-loss] Kerviel's initial 24-hour detention was extended to 48 while French law enforcement questioned him about possible accomplices.
[src:chrysler/2008-société-générale-trading-loss] The investigation later widened to encompass his personal cell phone records, and to explore possible links to other individuals working at rival banks and private investment firms who may be involved.
[src:chrysler/2008-société-générale-trading-loss] The police are investigating whether he worked alone, and whether any investors outside of Société Générale may have been tipped in advance.
[src:chrysler/2008-société-générale-trading-loss] Police are interested whether others were involved in either the trades themselves, or received notice of the bank's impending sell-off before the details of the scandal were publicly disclosed.
[src:chrysler/2008-société-générale-trading-loss] Kerviel was formally charged on January 28, 2008, with abuse of confidence and illegal access to computers.
[src:chrysler/2008-société-générale-trading-loss] He was released from custody a short time after.
[src:chrysler/2008-société-générale-trading-loss] The charges filed carry a maximum three-year prison term.
[src:chrysler/2008-société-générale-trading-loss] On January 29, 2008, investigating judges Renaud van Ryumbecke and Francoise Desset had rejected prosecutor Jean-Claude Marin's bid to charge Kerviel with the more serious crime of "attempted fraud" and refuse bail.
[src:chrysler/2008-société-générale-trading-loss] Société Générale characterizes Kerviel as a rogue trader and claims Kerviel worked these trades alone, and without its authorization.
[src:chrysler/2008-société-générale-trading-loss] Kerviel, in turn, told investigators that such practices are widespread and that getting a profit makes the hierarchy turn a blind eye.
[src:chrysler/2008-société-générale-trading-loss] The current investigation involves what is reported to be the largest fraud in banking history.
[src:chrysler/2008-société-générale-trading-loss] On 11 March 2008, Société Générale announced that another of their employees had been taken into custody in connection with the investigation of the fraud, and their headquarters searched by police.
[src:chrysler/2008-société-générale-trading-loss] On 5 October 2010, he was found guilty and sentenced to five years of prison, with two years suspended, full restitution of the $6.7b which was lost, and a permanent ban from working in financial services.
[src:chrysler/2008-société-générale-trading-loss] Caroline Guillaumin, a spokeswoman for Société Générale, stated that the restitution was "symbolic", and that the bank had no expectation that the sum would be paid.
[src:chrysler/2008-société-générale-trading-loss] Olivier Metzner, Kerviel's lawyer, described the sentence as "extraordinary" and said that Kerviel would appeal.
[src:chrysler/2008-société-générale-trading-loss] Kerviel's sentence was suspended until his appeal is completed.
[src:chrysler/2008-société-générale-trading-loss] On January 21, 2008, European stock markets suffered heavy losses of about 6%.
[src:chrysler/2008-société-générale-trading-loss] The sharp fall, which was followed by an emergency cut in the federal funds rate by the United States Federal Reserve on the following Tuesday (US markets were closed on the Monday for Martin Luther King Jr Day), came as Société Générale tried to close out positions built up by Kerviel.
[src:chrysler/2008-société-générale-trading-loss] This has led to speculation that stock market turbulence caused the Federal Reserve Board to cut the rate.
[src:chrysler/2008-société-générale-trading-loss] A Federal Reserve spokesperson denied the central bank knew of Société Générale's situation when it made its decision.
[src:chrysler/2008-société-générale-trading-loss] Minutes from the Federal Reserve meeting show no discussion of Société Générale.
[src:chrysler/2008-société-générale-trading-loss] It is estimated that over the period the total trading in futures and the cash market for the Euro Stoxx 50 was €544 billion.
[src:chrysler/2008-société-générale-trading-loss] This would make the unwinding of Kerviel's position account for five per cent or less of overall activity.
[src:chrysler/2008-société-générale-trading-loss] Société Générale's investment banking chief, Jean Pierre Mustier, acknowledged that the three days of forced selling played a role in the market's overall decline, but characterized that impact as "minimal".
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] During the period 2007–2009, the UK government intervened financially to support the UK banking sector, and four UK banks in particular.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] At peak, the cash cost of these interventions was £137 billion, paid to the banks in the form of loans and new capital.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] Most of this outlay has been recouped over the years.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] As at October 2021, the UK Office for Budget Responsibility reported the cost of these interventions as £33 billion, comprising a loss of £35.5 billion on the NatWest (formerly Royal Bank of Scotland (RBS)) rescue, offset by some net gains elsewhere.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] The first public indication of the crisis was in February 2007, when HSBC issued its first-ever profit warning as a result of losses incurred by its U.S. consumer finance arm.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] Later that year, in July 2007, two Bear Stearns hedge funds became insolvent.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] There followed a series of global events that led to the seizure of interbank credit markets.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] The UK retail bank Northern Rock, which relied heavily on short term funding, sought emergency assistance from the Bank of England.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] When this arrangement was publicised, the bank experienced the first run on a British bank in 150 years.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] In news reported around the world, customers of the bank were shown queuing outside branches to withdraw their deposits.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] In an effort to stop the panic, on 17 September 2007, the Chancellor of the Exchequer, Alistair Darling, announced the government would guarantee all Northern Rock deposits.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] From September 2007 to December 2009, the UK Government made further interventions to support the banking sector, and specifically to RBS (now NatWest), Lloyds Banking Group (LBG), Bradford & Bingley as well as Northern Rock.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] Northern Rock and Bradford & Bingley were both taken into full public ownership; RBS was taken into majority public ownership; and the government took a minority stake in LBG.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] In addition to cash support, the UK government enacted a number of other schemes involving financial guarantees with the aim of restoring confidence in the banking sector.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] These were contingent liabilities that did not involve cash outlays.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] The National Audit Office (NAO) estimated that total guarantees added up to over £1 trillion at peak support.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] As these guarantees were gradually withdrawn or expired, the outstanding sum under guarantee stood at £14 billion as at 31 March 2018.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] Subsequently, broadly similar measures were introduced by the United States and the European Union in response to the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] Later that year, in July 2007, two Bear Stearns hedge funds became insolvent, and in August 2007, French bank BNP Paribas froze three investment funds.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] These events initiated a seizure in the wholesale interbank credit markets.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] On 14 August 2007 the FSA disclosed concerns about the UK mortgage bank Northern Rock, which relied heavily on such markets in its funding model, to HM Treasury and the Bank of England.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] On 13 September the BBC reported that Northern Rock had been granted emergency financial support by the Bank of England in its role as lender of last resort.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] This triggered the first run on a UK bank in 150 years, that was ended only when HM Treasury announced, on 20 September, that the UK government would guarantee all existing Northern Rock retail deposits.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] The following month, the guarantee was extended to all new deposits.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] In February 2008, Northern Rock was taken into full public ownership.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] In April 2008, the Bank of England launched the Special Liquidity Scheme, allowing banks to swap mortgage-backed assets for Treasury bonds, so providing more trusted collateral for accessing market liquidity.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] The same month, Royal Bank of Scotland launched a £12 billion rights issue to supplement its equity capital.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] In September 2008, the US government launched bail-out rescues of the US mortgage lenders Fannie Mae (Federal National Mortgage Association) and Freddie Mac (Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corporation).
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] In 2008 Lehman Brothers was the fourth largest US investment bank, with worldwide operations.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] Its two principal business units were the broker dealers Lehman Brothers Inc (LBI), based in New York, and Lehman Brothers International (Europe) (LBIE), based in London.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] The cash resources of the Lehman Group were managed centrally in New York by the parent company, Lehman Brothers Holdings Inc.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] Following a deterioration in LBHI's financial position, on the afternoon of Sunday 14 September 2008, the directors of Lehman Brothers International (Europe) Ltd (LBIE) sought assurances from LBHI that payments due to be made on its behalf on the following business day would be made.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] At approximately 12.30 am on 15 September, LBHI informed LBIE that it was preparing to file for Chapter 11 Bankruptcy protection under US law and that it was therefore no longer in a position to make payments to or on behalf of LBIE.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] Accordingly, overnight preparations were made for a number of UK based Lehman companies to protect their interests by seeking an Administration Order under UK law.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] This order was granted by a UK judge at 7.56 am on Monday 15 September 2008.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] The immediate impact of the failure of the LBIE business in particular included 142,000 unsettled securities trades to which LBIE was a counterparty, of which approximately 83,500 were trades to be settled in Europe, 45,000 in Asia and 12,500 in the US.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] These were frozen and would remain so for several years.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] The Lehman collapse initiated a period of significant market turmoil.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] This was caused by complex financial interrelationships between the major banks, since assets on the Lehman balance sheet were inaccessible by counterparties, creating a domino effect in financial markets.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] Following the market disruption caused by the Lehman collapse, attention turned to HBOS, then the UK's largest mortgage lender.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] The bank had first appeared on the HM Treasury watch list after the Northern Rock problems surfaced, when it became clear that the HBOS funding model closely resembled that of Northern Rock.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] The bank was offering highly competitive and unprofitable housing market loans, combined with aggressive and high risk commercial lending.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] By July 2008, profits had halved and bad debts were up by a third.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] On 16 September HBOS saw 33 per cent of its value wiped out in a single day.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] The Financial Services Authority (FSA), the UK financial services regulator, responded by imposing a temporary ban on short selling of shares.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] At the same time, the UK government brokered an agreement with Lloyds Bank to acquire HBOS in a private sector deal.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] This was announced three days after the Lehman Brothers collapse, on 18 September.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] By the end of September 2008, Mervyn King, Governor of the Bank of England, Adair Turner, Chairman of the FSA, and Alistair Darling agreed that plans needed to be prepared for the recapitalisation of the banking system.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] Until that point, the crisis had primarily been one of liquidity, but the problem had now shifted to one of lack of capital.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] The only realistic source of new capital was the UK government.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] Darling instructed the Treasury to prepare a recapitalisation plan that envisaged the injection of billions of pounds into UK banks in return for equity.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] This would be financed by UK government bond sales.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] On 7 October 2008, following a 35% plunge in the bank's share price, dealing in the bank's shares was suspended.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] The bank Chairman, Tom McKillop, contacted the Chancellor of the Exchequer, Alistair Darling, to advise that the bank was within hours of running out of money.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] This was the decisive event that triggered the implementation of the recapitalisation plan.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] The intervention plan provided for several sources of funding to be made available to an aggregate total of £137 billion in cash injections and loans at peak, and a further £1,029 billion in guarantees at peak.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] As at October 2021, the OBR reported the current cost of these interventions as £33 billion, comprising a loss of £35.5 billion on the NatWest (formerly Royal Bank of Scotland) rescue, offset by some net gains elsewhere.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] Through the Bank Recapitalisation Fund, the government bought a combination of ordinary shares and preference shares in the affected banks.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] The amount and proportion of the stake taken in any one bank was negotiated with the individual bank.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] Banks that accepted rescue packages had restrictions on executive pay and dividends to existing shareholders, as well as a mandate to offer reasonable credit to homeowners and small businesses.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] The long-term government plan was to offset the cost of this program by receiving dividends from these shares, and in the long run, to sell the shares after a market recovery.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] This plan covered the possibility of underwriting new issues of shares by any participating bank.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] The plan was characterised as, in effect, full or partial nationalisation.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] The Credit Guarantee Scheme formed part of the UK government's banking intervention measures announced on 8 October 2008, becoming operational on 13 October 2008.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] The scheme was designed to allow banks to issue debt guaranteed by the government, with the intention of enabling them to borrow more, and more cheaply, and hence lend more.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] The banks that participated in the scheme included RBS, Lloyds, Barclays, Bank of Scotland, Nationwide Building Society, Clydesdale Bank, Tesco Personal Finance, Yorkshire Building Society, and Skipton Building Society.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] The Scheme was closed to new issuance on 28 February 2010 and was finally closed when the final guarantee expired on 26 October 2012.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] The Special Liquidity Scheme (SLS) was launched by the Bank of England on 21 April 2008.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] The SLS allowed banks to swap mortgage-backed and other securities for UK Treasury Bills.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] This was designed to allow easier access to market liquidity by using UK Treasury securities as collateral.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] The background to the scheme was the market closure for many securities, leaving assets on bank balance sheets which were unable to be sold or to be pledged as security to raise funds.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] This contributed to a market seizure where banks became reluctant to make new loans, even to each other.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] Under the SLS banks were provided with the means to swap illiquid assets, such as mortgage-backed securities, of designated quality for Treasury Bills.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] The SLS was closed in January 2012 when the last of the SLS transactions expired.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] The Bank of England Asset Purchase Facility, more commonly known as quantitative easing (QE), was introduced in 2009.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] This was primarily designed as an instrument of monetary policy.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] The mechanism required the Bank of England to purchase government bonds on the secondary market, financed by the creation of new central bank money.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] This would have the effect of increasing the asset prices of the bonds purchased, thereby lowering yields and dampening longer term interest rates.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] The aim of the policy was initially to ease liquidity constraints in the sterling reserves system, but evolved into a wider policy to provide economic stimulus.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] QE was enacted in six tranches between 2009 and 2020.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] At its peak in 2020, the portfolio totalled £895 billion, comprising £875 billion of UK government bonds and £20 billion of high grade commercial bonds.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] In February 2022 the Bank of England announced its intention to commence winding down the QE portfolio.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] Initially this would be achieved by not replacing tranches of maturing bonds, and would later be accelerated through active bond sales.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] In August 2022 the Bank of England reiterated its intention to accelerate the QE wind down through active bond sales.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] This policy was affirmed in an exchange of letters between the Bank of England and the UK Chancellor of the Exchequer in September 2022.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] Between February 2022 and September 2022, a total of £37.1bn of government bonds matured, reducing the outstanding stock from £875.0bn at the end of 2021 to £837.9bn.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] In addition, a total of £1.1bn of corporate bonds matured, reducing the stock from £20.0bn to £18.9bn, with sales of the remaining stock planned to begin on 27 September.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] On 28 September 2022 the Bank of England issued a Market Notice announcing its intention to "carry out purchases of long dated gilts in a temporary and targeted way".
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] This was in response to market conditions in which the sterling exchange rate and bond asset pricing were significantly disrupted following a UK government fiscal statement.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] The Bank stated its announcement would apply to conventional gilts of residual maturity greater than 20 years in the secondary market.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] The existing constraints applicable to QE bond purchases would continue to apply.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] The funding of the purchases would be met from central bank reserves, but would be segregated in a different portfolio from existing asset purchases.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] The Bank also announced that its annual £80bn target to reduce the existing QE portfolio remained unchanged but, in the light of current market conditions, the beginning of gilt sale operations would be postponed to 31 October 2022.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] The plan was open to all UK incorporated banks and all building societies, including the following: Abbey, Barclays, Clydesdale Bank, HBOS, HSBC, Lloyds, Nationwide Building Society, Royal Bank of Scotland, and Standard Chartered.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] The extent to which different banks participated varied according to their needs.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] HSBC Group issued a statement announcing it was injecting £750 m of capital into the UK bank and therefore has "no plans to utilise the UK government's recapitalisation initiative ... [as] the Group remains one of the most strongly capitalised and liquid banks in the world".
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] Standard Chartered also declared its support for the scheme but its intention not to participate in the capital injection element.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] Barclays raised its own new capital from private investors.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] The total UK government investment in RBS was £45.8 billion, with public ownership peaking at 84%.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] The average price per share paid by the Treasury was 499 pence, after receiving income from redeeming the preference shares.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] In August 2015 the UK government began the process of selling its RBS shares.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] It sold a 5.4% stake at an average of 330p per share.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] This brought its shareholding down to 72.9%.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] This transaction represented a loss of £1.9 billion (£1.1 billion excluding financing) to UK taxpayers.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] A second sale took place in June 2018, when the UK government disposed of second tranche of shares, representing a 7.7% stake, at an average price of 271p per share.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] This brought its shareholding down to 62.4%.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] In both cases, the government sold well below the average price of 499p per share it had paid, with the June 2018 transaction representing a loss of £2.1 billion to UK taxpayers.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] In March 2021 the UK government sold a further tranche of 590 million shares in NatWest at a price of 190.5p per share.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] This was followed by an announcement in July 2021 that the UK government would carry out open market sales in NatWest for a year from August 2021.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] By January 2022, it had sold 170.4 million shares in the NatWest Group totalling about £420 million, reducing its stake in the bank to 51%.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] After further sales in 2022, the UK government's RBS shareholding reduced below 50% for the first time since 2008, from 51% to 48.1%.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] This involved 550 million shares in NatWest at an average price of 220.5p per share, realising £1.2 billion.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] HBOS and Lloyds together raised £17 billion, £8.5 billion in preference shares and a further £8.5 billion issue of ordinary shares.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] The Fund purchased the preference shares outright, for a total £13.5 billion investment, and underwrote the issues of ordinary shares.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] Bradford & Bingley was nationalised by the UK government on 29 September 2008.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] The bank was divided into two businesses after the takeover.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] The depositor base of 2.7m customers and its network of 197 leasehold branches were sold to Santander Bank for £612 million.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] The Bradford & Bingley mortgage book, along with its equivalent at Northern Rock (Asset Management) were brought together under a single holding company, UK Asset Resolution (UKAR).
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] The Bank of England extended emergency loans totalling £25 billion to Northern Rock after it was unable to continue funding its loan book with wholesale financing in 2007.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] This triggered a public run on the bank.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] Attempts were made to find a private sector buyer.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] When these failed, Northern Rock was nationalised in February 2008.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] After further losses emerged, HM Treasury devised a strategy to divide Northern Rock into a "good bank" and "bad bank." The "good bank" was Northern Rock plc, which was responsible for holding and servicing all pre-existing customer savings accounts and some pre-existing mortgage accounts.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] Northern Rock plc received additional capital of £1.4 billion of equity from the UK government.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] The strategy was to prepare the bank for sale into the private sector.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] The "bad bank" was Northern Rock (Asset Management) plc, which held and serviced the closed mortgage book.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] On 1 October 2010, the UK government established of UK Asset Resolution as a holding company to manage and run down the assets of Northern Rock (Asset Management) plc alongside those of Bradford & Bingley.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] On 1 January 2012, Virgin Money purchased Northern Rock plc, and in July 2012 additionally purchased a substantial tranche of Northern Rock (Asset Management) mortgages from UKAR.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] Alistair Darling, the Chancellor of the Exchequer, told the House of Commons in a statement on 8 October 2008 that the proposals were "designed to restore confidence in the banking system", and that the funding would "put the banks on a stronger footing".
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] Darling said in 2018 that the country was hours away from a breakdown of law and order if the Royal Bank of Scotland had not been bailed out and people could not access money.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] On 8 October 2008 there was a strategic and co-ordinated global effort by seven central banks to calm the financial crisis, by cutting interest rates by 0.5%.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] The banks were all members of the OECD and included the Bank of England, the European Central Bank and the US Federal Reserve along with central banks in China, Switzerland, Canada and Sweden.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] The British rescue plan differed from the initial United States' $700 billion bailout under the Emergency Economic Stabilization Act of 2008, which was announced on 3 October and entitled the Troubled Asset Relief Program (TARP).
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] The £50bn being invested by the UK Government saw them purchasing shares in the banks, whereas the American program was primarily devoted to the U.S. government purchasing the mortgage backed securities of the American banks which were not able to be sold in the secondary mortgage securities market.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] The U.S. program required the U.S. government to take an equity interest in financial organisations selling their securities into the TARP but did not address the fundamental solvency problem faced by the banking sector; rather was aimed at tackling the immediate funding shortfall.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] The UK package tackled both solvency, through the £50bn recapitalisation plan, and funding, through the government guarantee for banks' debt issuances and the expansion of the Bank of England's Special Liquidity Scheme.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] Announced on 14 October, the U.S. subsequently undertook investments in banks through the Capital Purchase Program and the FDIC guaranteed banks' debt through the Temporary Lending Guarantee Program.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] Paul Krugman, writing in his column for *The New York Times*, stated that "Mr Brown and Alistair Darling, the Chancellor of the Exchequer have defined the character of the worldwide rescue effort, with other wealthy nations playing catch-up." He also stated that "Luckily for the world economy,...
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] Gordon Brown and his officials are making sense,...
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] And they may have shown us the way through this crisis." Other commentators noted that although the capitalist model should have allowed inefficient businesses to go bust, the banks were "too big to fail".
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] The British banking bail-out example was closely followed by the rest of Europe, as well as the U.S Government, who on 14 October 2008 announced a $250bn (£143bn) Capital Purchase Program to buy stakes in a wide variety of banks in an effort to restore confidence in the sector.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] The money came from the $700bn bail-out package approved by U.S. lawmakers earlier that month.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] A wave of international action to address the financial crisis affected stock markets around the world.
[src:chrysler/2008-united-kingdom-bank-rescue-package] Although shares in the affected banks fell, the Dow Jones went up by more than 900 points, or 11.1 per cent, while London shares also bounced back, with the FTSE 100 Index closing more than 8 per cent higher on 13 October 2008.
[src:chrysler/chrysler-p01] The original Chrysler Corporation was founded in 1925 by Walter Chrysler from the remains of the Maxwell Motor Company.
[src:chrysler/chrysler-p01] In 1998, it merged with Daimler-Benz, which renamed itself DaimlerChrysler but in 2007 sold off its Chrysler stake.
[src:chrysler/chrysler-p01] The company operated as Chrysler LLC through 2009, then as Chrysler Group LLC.
[src:chrysler/chrysler-p01] In 2014, it was acquired by Fiat S.p.A.; it subsequently operated as a subsidiary of the new Fiat Chrysler Automobiles (FCA), then as a subsidiary of Stellantis, the company formed from the 2021 merger of FCA and PSA Group (Peugeot Société Anonyme).
[src:chrysler/chrysler-p01] After founding the company, Walter Chrysler used General Motors (GM)'s brand diversification and hierarchy strategy that he knew of when he worked at its Buick division.
[src:chrysler/chrysler-p01] He then acquired Fargo Trucks and the Dodge Brothers Company, and created the Plymouth and DeSoto brands in 1928.
[src:chrysler/chrysler-p01] Facing postwar declines in market share, productivity, and profitability, as GM and Ford were growing, Chrysler borrowed $250 million in 1954 from Prudential Insurance to pay for expansion and updated car designs.
[src:chrysler/chrysler-p01] Chrysler expanded into Europe by taking control of French, British, and Spanish auto companies in the 1960s; but in 1978 Chrysler Europe was sold to PSA Peugeot Citroën for a nominal $1.
[src:chrysler/chrysler-p01] The company struggled to adapt to changing markets, increased U.S. import competition, and safety and environmental regulation in the 1970s.
[src:chrysler/chrysler-p01] It began an engineering partnership with Mitsubishi Motors, and began selling Mitsubishi vehicles branded as Dodge and Plymouth in North America.
[src:chrysler/chrysler-p01] On the verge of bankruptcy in the late 1970s, it was saved by $1.5 billion in loan guarantees from the U.S. government.
[src:chrysler/chrysler-p01] New CEO Lee Iacocca was credited with returning the company to profitability in the 1980s.
[src:chrysler/chrysler-p01] In 1985, Diamond-Star Motors was created, further expanding the Chrysler-Mitsubishi relationship.
[src:chrysler/chrysler-p01] In 1987, Chrysler acquired American Motors Corporation (AMC), which brought the profitable Jeep, as well as the newly formed Eagle, brands under the Chrysler umbrella.
[src:chrysler/chrysler-p01] In 1998, Chrysler merged with German automaker Daimler-Benz to form DaimlerChrysler AG; the merger proved contentious with investors.
